411/**
412 * Structure to describe a region of text to be encrypted or decrypted.
413 *
414 * The @a flags member describes the type of the iov.
415 * The @a data member points to the memory that will be manipulated.
416 * All iov APIs take a pointer to the first element of an array of krb5_crypto_iov's
417 * along with the size of that array. Buffer contents are manipulated in-place;
418 * data is overwritten. Callers must allocate the right number of krb5_crypto_iov
419 * structures before calling into an iov API.
420 */
421typedef struct _krb5_crypto_iov {
422 krb5_cryptotype flags; /**< @ref KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE type of the iov */
423 krb5_data data;
424} krb5_crypto_iov;

427#define ENCTYPE_NULL 0x0000

429#define ENCTYPE_DES_CBC_MD4 0x0002 /**< DES cbc mode with RSA-MD4 */

476/*
477 * The following are entropy source designations. Whenever
478 * krb5_C_random_add_entropy is called, one of these source ids is passed in.
479 * This allows the library to better estimate bits of entropy in the sample and
480 * to keep track of what sources of entropy have contributed enough entropy.
481 * Sources marked internal MUST NOT be used by applications outside the
482 * Kerberos library
483 */
484
485enum {
486 KRB5_C_RANDSOURCE_OLDAPI = 0, /*calls to krb5_C_RANDOM_SEED (INTERNAL)*/
487 KRB5_C_RANDSOURCE_OSRAND = 1, /* /dev/random or equivalent (internal)*/
488 KRB5_C_RANDSOURCE_TRUSTEDPARTY = 2, /* From KDC or other trusted party*/
489 /*
490 * This source should be used carefully; data in this category
491 * should be from a third party trusted to give random bits
492 * For example keys issued by the KDC in the application server.
493 */
494 KRB5_C_RANDSOURCE_TIMING = 3, /* Timing of operations*/
495 KRB5_C_RANDSOURCE_EXTERNAL_PROTOCOL = 4, /*Protocol data possibly from attacker*/
496 KRB5_C_RANDSOURCE_MAX = 5 /*Do not use; maximum source ID*/
497};

514/**
515 * Encrypt data using a key (operates on keyblock).
516 *
517 * @param [in] context Library context
518 * @param [in] key Encryption key
519 * @param [in] usage Key usage (see @ref KRB5_KEYUSAGE types)
520 * @param [in,out] cipher_state Cipher state; specify NULL if not needed
521 * @param [in] input Data to be encrypted
522 * @param [out] output Encrypted data
523 *
524 * This function encrypts the data block @a input and stores the output into @a
525 * output. The actual encryption key will be derived from @a key and @a usage
526 * if key derivation is specified for the encryption type. If non-null, @a
527 * cipher_state specifies the beginning state for the encryption operation, and
528 * is updated with the state to be passed as input to the next operation.
529 *
530 * @note The caller must initialize @a output and allocate at least enough
531 * space for the result (using krb5_c_encrypt_length() to determine the amount
532 * of space needed). @a output->length will be set to the actual length of the
533 * ciphertext.
534 *
535 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
536 */
537krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
538krb5_c_encrypt(krb5_context context, const krb5_keyblock *key,
539 krb5_keyusage usage, const krb5_data *cipher_state,
540 const krb5_data *input, krb5_enc_data *output);
541
542/**
543 * Decrypt data using a key (operates on keyblock).
544 *
545 * @param [in] context Library context
546 * @param [in] key Encryption key
547 * @param [in] usage Key usage (see @ref KRB5_KEYUSAGE types)
548 * @param [in,out] cipher_state Cipher state; specify NULL if not needed
549 * @param [in] input Encrypted data
550 * @param [out] output Decrypted data
551 *
552 * This function decrypts the data block @a input and stores the output into @a
553 * output. The actual decryption key will be derived from @a key and @a usage
554 * if key derivation is specified for the encryption type. If non-null, @a
555 * cipher_state specifies the beginning state for the decryption operation, and
556 * is updated with the state to be passed as input to the next operation.
557 *
558 * @note The caller must initialize @a output and allocate at least enough
559 * space for the result. The usual practice is to allocate an output buffer as
560 * long as the ciphertext, and let krb5_c_decrypt() trim @a output->length.
561 * For some enctypes, the resulting @a output->length may include padding
562 * bytes.
563 *
564 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
565 */
566krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
567krb5_c_decrypt(krb5_context context, const krb5_keyblock *key,
568 krb5_keyusage usage, const krb5_data *cipher_state,
569 const krb5_enc_data *input, krb5_data *output);
570
571/**
572 * Compute encrypted data length.
573 *
574 * @param [in] context Library context
575 * @param [in] enctype Encryption type
576 * @param [in] inputlen Length of the data to be encrypted
577 * @param [out] length Length of the encrypted data
578 *
579 * This function computes the length of the ciphertext produced by encrypting
580 * @a inputlen bytes including padding, confounder, and checksum.
581 *
582 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
583 */
584krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
585krb5_c_encrypt_length(krb5_context context, krb5_enctype enctype,
586 size_t inputlen, size_t *length);

625krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
626krb5_c_init_state(krb5_context context, const krb5_keyblock *key,
627 krb5_keyusage usage, krb5_data *new_state);

629/**
630 * Free a cipher state previously allocated by krb5_c_init_state().
631 *

636 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes

642/**
643 * Generate enctype-specific pseudo-random bytes.
644 *
645 * @param [in] context Library context
646 * @param [in] keyblock Key
647 * @param [in] input Input data
648 * @param [out] output Output data
649 *
650 * This function selects a pseudo-random function based on @a keyblock and
651 * computes its value over @a input, placing the result into @a output.
652 * The caller must preinitialize @a output and allocate space for the
653 * result, using krb5_c_prf_length() to determine the required length.
654 *
655 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
656 */
657krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
658krb5_c_prf(krb5_context context, const krb5_keyblock *keyblock,
659 krb5_data *input, krb5_data *output);
660
661/**
662 * Get the output length of pseudo-random functions for an encryption type.
663 *
664 * @param [in] context Library context
665 * @param [in] enctype Encryption type
666 * @param [out] len Length of PRF output
667 *
668 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
669 */
670krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
671krb5_c_prf_length(krb5_context context, krb5_enctype enctype, size_t *len);
672
673/**
674 * Generate pseudo-random bytes using RFC 6113 PRF+.
675 *
676 * @param [in] context Library context
677 * @param [in] k KDC contribution key
678 * @param [in] input Input data
679 * @param [out] output Pseudo-random output buffer
680 *
681 * This function fills @a output with PRF+(k, input) as defined in RFC 6113
682 * section 5.1. The caller must preinitialize @a output and allocate the
683 * desired amount of space. The length of the pseudo-random output will match
684 * the length of @a output.
685 *
686 * @note RFC 4402 defines a different PRF+ operation. This function does not
687 * implement that operation.
688 *
689 * @return 0 on success, @c E2BIG if output->length is too large for PRF+ to
690 * generate, @c ENOMEM on allocation failure, or an error code from
691 * krb5_c_prf()
692 */
693krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
694krb5_c_prfplus(krb5_context context, const krb5_keyblock *k,
695 const krb5_data *input, krb5_data *output);
696
697/**
698 * Derive a key using some input data (via RFC 6113 PRF+).
699 *
700 * @param [in] context Library context
701 * @param [in] k KDC contribution key
702 * @param [in] input Input string
703 * @param [in] enctype Output key enctype (or @c ENCTYPE_NULL)
704 * @param [out] out Derived keyblock
705 *
706 * This function uses PRF+ as defined in RFC 6113 to derive a key from another
707 * key and an input string. If @a enctype is @c ENCTYPE_NULL, the output key
708 * will have the same enctype as the input key.
709 */
710krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
711krb5_c_derive_prfplus(krb5_context context, const krb5_keyblock *k,
712 const krb5_data *input, krb5_enctype enctype,
713 krb5_keyblock **out);
714
715/**
716 * Compute the KRB-FX-CF2 combination of two keys and pepper strings.
717 *
718 * @param [in] context Library context
719 * @param [in] k1 KDC contribution key
720 * @param [in] pepper1 String "PKINIT"
721 * @param [in] k2 Reply key
722 * @param [in] pepper2 String "KeyExchange"
723 * @param [out] out Output key
724 *
725 * This function computes the KRB-FX-CF2 function over its inputs and places
726 * the results in a newly allocated keyblock. This function is simple in that
727 * it assumes that @a pepper1 and @a pepper2 are C strings with no internal
728 * nulls and that the enctype of the result will be the same as that of @a k1.
729 * @a k1 and @a k2 may be of different enctypes.
730 *
731 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
732 */
733krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
734krb5_c_fx_cf2_simple(krb5_context context,
735 const krb5_keyblock *k1, const char *pepper1,
736 const krb5_keyblock *k2, const char *pepper2,
737 krb5_keyblock **out);
738

892/**
893 * Compute a checksum (operates on keyblock).
894 *
895 * @param [in] context Library context
896 * @param [in] cksumtype Checksum type (0 for mandatory type)
897 * @param [in] key Encryption key for a keyed checksum
898 * @param [in] usage Key usage (see @ref KRB5_KEYUSAGE types)
899 * @param [in] input Input data
900 * @param [out] cksum Generated checksum
901 *
902 * This function computes a checksum of type @a cksumtype over @a input, using
903 * @a key if the checksum type is a keyed checksum. If @a cksumtype is 0 and
904 * @a key is non-null, the checksum type will be the mandatory-to-implement
905 * checksum type for the key's encryption type. The actual checksum key will
906 * be derived from @a key and @a usage if key derivation is specified for the
907 * checksum type. The newly created @a cksum must be released by calling
908 * krb5_free_checksum_contents() when it is no longer needed.
909 *
910 * @note This function is similar to krb5_k_make_checksum(), but operates
911 * on keyblock @a key.
912 *
913 * @sa krb5_c_verify_checksum()
914 *
915 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
916 */
917krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
918krb5_c_make_checksum(krb5_context context, krb5_cksumtype cksumtype,
919 const krb5_keyblock *key, krb5_keyusage usage,
920 const krb5_data *input, krb5_checksum *cksum);
921
922/**
923 * Verify a checksum (operates on keyblock).
924 *
925 * @param [in] context Library context
926 * @param [in] key Encryption key for a keyed checksum
927 * @param [in] usage @a key usage
928 * @param [in] data Data to be used to compute a new checksum
929 * using @a key to compare @a cksum against
930 * @param [in] cksum Checksum to be verified
931 * @param [out] valid Non-zero for success, zero for failure
932 *
933 * This function verifies that @a cksum is a valid checksum for @a data. If
934 * the checksum type of @a cksum is a keyed checksum, @a key is used to verify
935 * the checksum. If the checksum type in @a cksum is 0 and @a key is not NULL,
936 * the mandatory checksum type for @a key will be used. The actual checksum
937 * key will be derived from @a key and @a usage if key derivation is specified
938 * for the checksum type.
939 *
940 * @note This function is similar to krb5_k_verify_checksum(), but operates
941 * on keyblock @a key.
942 *
943 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
944 */
945krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
946krb5_c_verify_checksum(krb5_context context, const krb5_keyblock *key,
947 krb5_keyusage usage, const krb5_data *data,
948 const krb5_checksum *cksum, krb5_boolean *valid);
949
950/**
951 * Return the length of checksums for a checksum type.
952 *
953 * @param [in] context Library context
954 * @param [in] cksumtype Checksum type
955 * @param [out] length Checksum length
956 *
957 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
958 */
959krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
960krb5_c_checksum_length(krb5_context context, krb5_cksumtype cksumtype,
961 size_t *length);
962
963/**
964 * Return a list of keyed checksum types usable with an encryption type.
965 *
966 * @param [in] context Library context
967 * @param [in] enctype Encryption type
968 * @param [out] count Count of allowable checksum types
969 * @param [out] cksumtypes Array of allowable checksum types
970 *
971 * Use krb5_free_cksumtypes() to free @a cksumtypes when it is no longer
972 * needed.
973 *
974 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
975 */
976krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
977krb5_c_keyed_checksum_types(krb5_context context, krb5_enctype enctype,

1101/**
1102 * Fill in a checksum element in IOV array (operates on keyblock)
1103 *
1104 * @param [in] context Library context
1105 * @param [in] cksumtype Checksum type (0 for mandatory type)
1106 * @param [in] key Encryption key for a keyed checksum
1107 * @param [in] usage Key usage (see @ref KRB5_KEYUSAGE types)
1108 * @param [in,out] data IOV array
1109 * @param [in] num_data Size of @a data
1110 *
1111 * Create a checksum in the #KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE_CHECKSUM element over
1112 * #KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE_DATA and #KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE_SIGN_ONLY chunks in @a data.
1113 * Only the #KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE_CHECKSUM region is modified.
1114 *
1115 * @note This function is similar to krb5_k_make_checksum_iov(), but operates
1116 * on keyblock @a key.
1117 *
1118 * @sa krb5_c_verify_checksum_iov()
1119 *
1120 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
1121 */
1122krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1123krb5_c_make_checksum_iov(krb5_context context, krb5_cksumtype cksumtype,
1124 const krb5_keyblock *key, krb5_keyusage usage,
1125 krb5_crypto_iov *data, size_t num_data);
1126
1127/**
1128 * Validate a checksum element in IOV array (operates on keyblock).
1129 *
1130 * @param [in] context Library context
1131 * @param [in] cksumtype Checksum type (0 for mandatory type)
1132 * @param [in] key Encryption key for a keyed checksum
1133 * @param [in] usage Key usage (see @ref KRB5_KEYUSAGE types)
1134 * @param [in] data IOV array
1135 * @param [in] num_data Size of @a data
1136 * @param [out] valid Non-zero for success, zero for failure
1137 *
1138 * Confirm that the checksum in the #KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE_CHECKSUM element is a
1139 * valid checksum of the #KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE_DATA and #KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE_SIGN_ONLY
1140 * regions in the iov.
1141 *
1142 * @note This function is similar to krb5_k_verify_checksum_iov(), but operates
1143 * on keyblock @a key.
1144 *
1145 * @sa krb5_c_make_checksum_iov()
1146 *
1147 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
1148 */
1149krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1150krb5_c_verify_checksum_iov(krb5_context context, krb5_cksumtype cksumtype,
1151 const krb5_keyblock *key, krb5_keyusage usage,
1152 const krb5_crypto_iov *data, size_t num_data,
1153 krb5_boolean *valid);

1155/**
1156 * Encrypt data in place supporting AEAD (operates on keyblock).
1157 *
1158 * @param [in] context Library context
1159 * @param [in] keyblock Encryption key
1160 * @param [in] usage Key usage (see @ref KRB5_KEYUSAGE types)
1161 * @param [in] cipher_state Cipher state; specify NULL if not needed
1162 * @param [in,out] data IOV array. Modified in-place.
1163 * @param [in] num_data Size of @a data
1164 *
1165 * This function encrypts the data block @a data and stores the output in-place.
1166 * The actual encryption key will be derived from @a keyblock and @a usage
1167 * if key derivation is specified for the encryption type. If non-null, @a
1168 * cipher_state specifies the beginning state for the encryption operation, and
1169 * is updated with the state to be passed as input to the next operation.
1170 * The caller must allocate the right number of krb5_crypto_iov
1171 * structures before calling into this API.
1172 *
1173 * @note On return from a krb5_c_encrypt_iov() call, the @a data->length in the
1174 * iov structure are adjusted to reflect actual lengths of the ciphertext used.
1175 * For example, if the padding length is too large, the length will be reduced.
1176 * Lengths are never increased.
1177 *
1178 * @note This function is similar to krb5_k_encrypt_iov(), but operates
1179 * on keyblock @a keyblock.
1180 *
1181 * @sa krb5_c_decrypt_iov()
1182 *
1183 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
1184 */
1185krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1186krb5_c_encrypt_iov(krb5_context context, const krb5_keyblock *keyblock,
1187 krb5_keyusage usage, const krb5_data *cipher_state,
1188 krb5_crypto_iov *data, size_t num_data);
1189
1190/**
1191 * Decrypt data in place supporting AEAD (operates on keyblock).
1192 *
1193 * @param [in] context Library context
1194 * @param [in] keyblock Encryption key
1195 * @param [in] usage Key usage (see @ref KRB5_KEYUSAGE types)
1196 * @param [in] cipher_state Cipher state; specify NULL if not needed
1197 * @param [in,out] data IOV array. Modified in-place.
1198 * @param [in] num_data Size of @a data
1199 *
1200 * This function decrypts the data block @a data and stores the output in-place.
1201 * The actual decryption key will be derived from @a keyblock and @a usage
1202 * if key derivation is specified for the encryption type. If non-null, @a
1203 * cipher_state specifies the beginning state for the decryption operation, and
1204 * is updated with the state to be passed as input to the next operation.
1205 * The caller must allocate the right number of krb5_crypto_iov
1206 * structures before calling into this API.
1207 *
1208 * @note On return from a krb5_c_decrypt_iov() call, the @a data->length in the
1209 * iov structure are adjusted to reflect actual lengths of the ciphertext used.
1210 * For example, if the padding length is too large, the length will be reduced.
1211 * Lengths are never increased.
1212 *
1213 * @note This function is similar to krb5_k_decrypt_iov(), but operates
1214 * on keyblock @a keyblock.
1215 *
1216 * @sa krb5_c_decrypt_iov()
1217 *
1218 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
1219 */
1220krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1221krb5_c_decrypt_iov(krb5_context context, const krb5_keyblock *keyblock,
1222 krb5_keyusage usage, const krb5_data *cipher_state,
1223 krb5_crypto_iov *data, size_t num_data);
1224
1225/**
1226 * Return a length of a message field specific to the encryption type.
1227 *
1228 * @param [in] context Library context
1229 * @param [in] enctype Encryption type
1230 * @param [in] type Type field (See @ref KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE types)
1231 * @param [out] size Length of the @a type specific to @a enctype
1232 *
1233 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
1234 */
1235krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1236krb5_c_crypto_length(krb5_context context, krb5_enctype enctype,
1237 krb5_cryptotype type, unsigned int *size);
1238
1239/**
1240 * Fill in lengths for header, trailer and padding in a IOV array.
1241 *
1242 * @param [in] context Library context
1243 * @param [in] enctype Encryption type
1244 * @param [in,out] data IOV array
1245 * @param [in] num_data Size of @a data
1246 *
1247 * Padding is set to the actual padding required based on the provided
1248 * @a data buffers. Typically this API is used after setting up the data
1249 * buffers and #KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE_SIGN_ONLY buffers, but before actually
1250 * allocating header, trailer and padding.
1251 *
1252 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
1253 */
1254krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1255krb5_c_crypto_length_iov(krb5_context context, krb5_enctype enctype,
1256 krb5_crypto_iov *data, size_t num_data);
1257
1258/**
1259 * Return a number of padding octets.
1260 *
1261 * @param [in] context Library context
1262 * @param [in] enctype Encryption type
1263 * @param [in] data_length Length of the plaintext to pad
1264 * @param [out] size Number of padding octets
1265 *
1266 * This function returns the number of the padding octets required to pad
1267 * @a data_length octets of plaintext.
1268 *
1269 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - KRB5_BAD_ENCTYPE
1270 */
1271krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1272krb5_c_padding_length(krb5_context context, krb5_enctype enctype,
1273 size_t data_length, unsigned int *size);

1275/**
1276 * Create a krb5_key from the enctype and key data in a keyblock.

1279 * @param [in] key_data Keyblock
1280 * @param [out] out Opaque key
1281 *
1282 * The reference count on a key @a out is set to 1.
1283 * Use krb5_k_free_key() to free @a out when it is no longer needed.
1284 *
1285 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - KRB5_BAD_ENCTYPE

1308/**
1309 * Encrypt data using a key (operates on opaque key).
1310 *
1311 * @param [in] context Library context
1312 * @param [in] key Encryption key
1313 * @param [in] usage Key usage (see @ref KRB5_KEYUSAGE types)
1314 * @param [in,out] cipher_state Cipher state; specify NULL if not needed
1315 * @param [in] input Data to be encrypted
1316 * @param [out] output Encrypted data
1317 *
1318 * This function encrypts the data block @a input and stores the output into @a
1319 * output. The actual encryption key will be derived from @a key and @a usage
1320 * if key derivation is specified for the encryption type. If non-null, @a
1321 * cipher_state specifies the beginning state for the encryption operation, and
1322 * is updated with the state to be passed as input to the next operation.
1323 *
1324 * @note The caller must initialize @a output and allocate at least enough
1325 * space for the result (using krb5_c_encrypt_length() to determine the amount
1326 * of space needed). @a output->length will be set to the actual length of the
1327 * ciphertext.
1328 *
1329 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
1330 */
1331krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1332krb5_k_encrypt(krb5_context context, krb5_key key, krb5_keyusage usage,
1333 const krb5_data *cipher_state, const krb5_data *input,
1334 krb5_enc_data *output);
1335
1336/**
1337 * Encrypt data in place supporting AEAD (operates on opaque key).
1338 *
1339 * @param [in] context Library context
1340 * @param [in] key Encryption key
1341 * @param [in] usage Key usage (see @ref KRB5_KEYUSAGE types)
1342 * @param [in] cipher_state Cipher state; specify NULL if not needed
1343 * @param [in,out] data IOV array. Modified in-place.
1344 * @param [in] num_data Size of @a data
1345 *
1346 * This function encrypts the data block @a data and stores the output in-place.
1347 * The actual encryption key will be derived from @a key and @a usage
1348 * if key derivation is specified for the encryption type. If non-null, @a
1349 * cipher_state specifies the beginning state for the encryption operation, and
1350 * is updated with the state to be passed as input to the next operation.
1351 * The caller must allocate the right number of krb5_crypto_iov
1352 * structures before calling into this API.
1353 *
1354 * @note On return from a krb5_c_encrypt_iov() call, the @a data->length in the
1355 * iov structure are adjusted to reflect actual lengths of the ciphertext used.
1356 * For example, if the padding length is too large, the length will be reduced.
1357 * Lengths are never increased.
1358 *
1359 * @note This function is similar to krb5_c_encrypt_iov(), but operates
1360 * on opaque key @a key.
1361 *
1362 * @sa krb5_k_decrypt_iov()
1363 *
1364 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
1365 */
1366krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1367krb5_k_encrypt_iov(krb5_context context, krb5_key key, krb5_keyusage usage,
1368 const krb5_data *cipher_state, krb5_crypto_iov *data,
1369 size_t num_data);

1371/**
1372 * Decrypt data using a key (operates on opaque key).
1373 *
1374 * @param [in] context Library context
1375 * @param [in] key Encryption key
1376 * @param [in] usage Key usage (see @ref KRB5_KEYUSAGE types)
1377 * @param [in,out] cipher_state Cipher state; specify NULL if not needed
1378 * @param [in] input Encrypted data
1379 * @param [out] output Decrypted data
1380 *
1381 * This function decrypts the data block @a input and stores the output into @a
1382 * output. The actual decryption key will be derived from @a key and @a usage
1383 * if key derivation is specified for the encryption type. If non-null, @a
1384 * cipher_state specifies the beginning state for the decryption operation, and
1385 * is updated with the state to be passed as input to the next operation.
1386 *
1387 * @note The caller must initialize @a output and allocate at least enough
1388 * space for the result. The usual practice is to allocate an output buffer as
1389 * long as the ciphertext, and let krb5_c_decrypt() trim @a output->length.
1390 * For some enctypes, the resulting @a output->length may include padding
1391 * bytes.
1392 *
1393 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
1394 */
1395krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1396krb5_k_decrypt(krb5_context context, krb5_key key, krb5_keyusage usage,
1397 const krb5_data *cipher_state, const krb5_enc_data *input,
1398 krb5_data *output);
1399
1400/**
1401 * Decrypt data in place supporting AEAD (operates on opaque key).
1402 *
1403 * @param [in] context Library context
1404 * @param [in] key Encryption key
1405 * @param [in] usage Key usage (see @ref KRB5_KEYUSAGE types)
1406 * @param [in] cipher_state Cipher state; specify NULL if not needed
1407 * @param [in,out] data IOV array. Modified in-place.
1408 * @param [in] num_data Size of @a data
1409 *
1410 * This function decrypts the data block @a data and stores the output in-place.
1411 * The actual decryption key will be derived from @a key and @a usage
1412 * if key derivation is specified for the encryption type. If non-null, @a
1413 * cipher_state specifies the beginning state for the decryption operation, and
1414 * is updated with the state to be passed as input to the next operation.
1415 * The caller must allocate the right number of krb5_crypto_iov
1416 * structures before calling into this API.
1417 *
1418 * @note On return from a krb5_c_decrypt_iov() call, the @a data->length in the
1419 * iov structure are adjusted to reflect actual lengths of the ciphertext used.
1420 * For example, if the padding length is too large, the length will be reduced.
1421 * Lengths are never increased.
1422 *
1423 * @note This function is similar to krb5_c_decrypt_iov(), but operates
1424 * on opaque key @a key.
1425 *
1426 * @sa krb5_k_encrypt_iov()
1427 *
1428 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
1429 */
1430krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1431krb5_k_decrypt_iov(krb5_context context, krb5_key key, krb5_keyusage usage,
1432 const krb5_data *cipher_state, krb5_crypto_iov *data,
1433 size_t num_data);
1434/**
1435 * Compute a checksum (operates on opaque key).
1436 *
1437 * @param [in] context Library context
1438 * @param [in] cksumtype Checksum type (0 for mandatory type)
1439 * @param [in] key Encryption key for a keyed checksum
1440 * @param [in] usage Key usage (see @ref KRB5_KEYUSAGE types)
1441 * @param [in] input Input data
1442 * @param [out] cksum Generated checksum
1443 *
1444 * This function computes a checksum of type @a cksumtype over @a input, using
1445 * @a key if the checksum type is a keyed checksum. If @a cksumtype is 0 and
1446 * @a key is non-null, the checksum type will be the mandatory-to-implement
1447 * checksum type for the key's encryption type. The actual checksum key will
1448 * be derived from @a key and @a usage if key derivation is specified for the
1449 * checksum type. The newly created @a cksum must be released by calling
1450 * krb5_free_checksum_contents() when it is no longer needed.
1451 *
1452 * @note This function is similar to krb5_c_make_checksum(), but operates
1453 * on opaque @a key.
1454 *
1455 * @sa krb5_c_verify_checksum()
1456 *
1457 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
1458 */
1459krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1460krb5_k_make_checksum(krb5_context context, krb5_cksumtype cksumtype,
1461 krb5_key key, krb5_keyusage usage, const krb5_data *input,
1462 krb5_checksum *cksum);
1463
1464/**
1465 * Fill in a checksum element in IOV array (operates on opaque key)
1466 *
1467 * @param [in] context Library context
1468 * @param [in] cksumtype Checksum type (0 for mandatory type)
1469 * @param [in] key Encryption key for a keyed checksum
1470 * @param [in] usage Key usage (see @ref KRB5_KEYUSAGE types)
1471 * @param [in,out] data IOV array
1472 * @param [in] num_data Size of @a data
1473 *
1474 * Create a checksum in the #KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE_CHECKSUM element over
1475 * #KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE_DATA and #KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE_SIGN_ONLY chunks in @a data.
1476 * Only the #KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE_CHECKSUM region is modified.
1477 *
1478 * @note This function is similar to krb5_c_make_checksum_iov(), but operates
1479 * on opaque @a key.
1480 *
1481 * @sa krb5_k_verify_checksum_iov()
1482 *
1483 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
1484 */
1485krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1486krb5_k_make_checksum_iov(krb5_context context, krb5_cksumtype cksumtype,
1487 krb5_key key, krb5_keyusage usage,
1488 krb5_crypto_iov *data, size_t num_data);
1489
1490/**
1491 * Verify a checksum (operates on opaque key).
1492 *
1493 * @param [in] context Library context
1494 * @param [in] key Encryption key for a keyed checksum
1495 * @param [in] usage @a key usage
1496 * @param [in] data Data to be used to compute a new checksum
1497 * using @a key to compare @a cksum against
1498 * @param [in] cksum Checksum to be verified
1499 * @param [out] valid Non-zero for success, zero for failure
1500 *
1501 * This function verifies that @a cksum is a valid checksum for @a data. If
1502 * the checksum type of @a cksum is a keyed checksum, @a key is used to verify
1503 * the checksum. If the checksum type in @a cksum is 0 and @a key is not NULL,
1504 * the mandatory checksum type for @a key will be used. The actual checksum
1505 * key will be derived from @a key and @a usage if key derivation is specified
1506 * for the checksum type.
1507 *
1508 * @note This function is similar to krb5_c_verify_checksum(), but operates
1509 * on opaque @a key.
1510 *
1511 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
1512 */
1513krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1514krb5_k_verify_checksum(krb5_context context, krb5_key key, krb5_keyusage usage,
1515 const krb5_data *data, const krb5_checksum *cksum,
1516 krb5_boolean *valid);
1517
1518/**
1519 * Validate a checksum element in IOV array (operates on opaque key).
1520 *
1521 * @param [in] context Library context
1522 * @param [in] cksumtype Checksum type (0 for mandatory type)
1523 * @param [in] key Encryption key for a keyed checksum
1524 * @param [in] usage Key usage (see @ref KRB5_KEYUSAGE types)
1525 * @param [in] data IOV array
1526 * @param [in] num_data Size of @a data
1527 * @param [out] valid Non-zero for success, zero for failure
1528 *
1529 * Confirm that the checksum in the #KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE_CHECKSUM element is a
1530 * valid checksum of the #KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE_DATA and #KRB5_CRYPTO_TYPE_SIGN_ONLY
1531 * regions in the iov.
1532 *
1533 * @note This function is similar to krb5_c_verify_checksum_iov(), but operates
1534 * on opaque @a key.
1535 *
1536 * @sa krb5_k_make_checksum_iov()
1537 *
1538 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
1539 */
1540krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1541krb5_k_verify_checksum_iov(krb5_context context, krb5_cksumtype cksumtype,
1542 krb5_key key, krb5_keyusage usage,
1543 const krb5_crypto_iov *data, size_t num_data,
1544 krb5_boolean *valid);
1545
1546/**
1547 * Generate enctype-specific pseudo-random bytes (operates on opaque key).
1548 *
1549 * @param [in] context Library context
1550 * @param [in] key Key
1551 * @param [in] input Input data
1552 * @param [out] output Output data
1553 *
1554 * This function selects a pseudo-random function based on @a key and
1555 * computes its value over @a input, placing the result into @a output.
1556 * The caller must preinitialize @a output and allocate space for the
1557 * result.
1558 *
1559 * @note This function is similar to krb5_c_prf(), but operates
1560 * on opaque @a key.
1561 *
1562 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
1563 */
1564krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
1565krb5_k_prf(krb5_context context, krb5_key key, krb5_data *input, krb5_data *output);

1654
1655/* kdc_options for kdc_request */
1656/* options is 32 bits; each host is responsible to put the 4 bytes
1657 representing these bits into net order before transmission */
1658/* #define KDC_OPT_RESERVED 0x80000000 */
1659#define KDC_OPT_FORWARDABLE 0x40000000
1660#define KDC_OPT_FORWARDED 0x20000000
1661#define KDC_OPT_PROXIABLE 0x10000000
1662#define KDC_OPT_PROXY 0x08000000
1663#define KDC_OPT_ALLOW_POSTDATE 0x04000000
1664#define KDC_OPT_POSTDATED 0x02000000
1665/* #define KDC_OPT_UNUSED 0x01000000 */
1666#define KDC_OPT_RENEWABLE 0x00800000
1667/* #define KDC_OPT_UNUSED 0x00400000 */
1668/* #define KDC_OPT_RESERVED 0x00200000 */
1669/* #define KDC_OPT_RESERVED 0x00100000 */
1670/* #define KDC_OPT_RESERVED 0x00080000 */
1671/* #define KDC_OPT_RESERVED 0x00040000 */
1672#define KDC_OPT_CNAME_IN_ADDL_TKT 0x00020000
1673#define KDC_OPT_CANONICALIZE 0x00010000
1674#define KDC_OPT_REQUEST_ANONYMOUS 0x00008000
1675/* #define KDC_OPT_RESERVED 0x00004000 */
1676/* #define KDC_OPT_RESERVED 0x00002000 */
1677/* #define KDC_OPT_RESERVED 0x00001000 */
1678/* #define KDC_OPT_RESERVED 0x00000800 */

2174 krb5_address *r_address; /**< Recipient address (optional) */
2175 krb5_cred_info **ticket_info;
2176} krb5_cred_enc_part;

2224/** @defgroup KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT
2225 * @{
2226 */
2227/** Prevent replays with timestamps and replay cache. */
2228#define KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_DO_TIME 0x00000001
2229/** Save timestamps for application. */
2230#define KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_RET_TIME 0x00000002
2231/** Prevent replays with sequence numbers. */
2232#define KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_DO_SEQUENCE 0x00000004
2233/** Save sequence numbers for application. */
2234#define KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_RET_SEQUENCE 0x00000008
2235#define KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_PERMIT_ALL 0x00000010
2236#define KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_USE_SUBKEY 0x00000020
2237/** @} */ /* end of KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT group */

2288/* Flags for krb5_cc_retrieve_cred. */
2289/** The requested lifetime must be at least as great as the time specified. */
2290#define KRB5_TC_MATCH_TIMES 0x00000001
2291/** The is_skey field must match exactly. */
2292#define KRB5_TC_MATCH_IS_SKEY 0x00000002
2293/** All the flags set in the match credentials must be set. */
2294#define KRB5_TC_MATCH_FLAGS 0x00000004
2295/** All the time fields must match exactly. */
2296#define KRB5_TC_MATCH_TIMES_EXACT 0x00000008
2297/** All the flags must match exactly. */
2298#define KRB5_TC_MATCH_FLAGS_EXACT 0x00000010
2299/** The authorization data must match. */
2300#define KRB5_TC_MATCH_AUTHDATA 0x00000020
2301/** Only the name portion of the principal name must match. */
2302#define KRB5_TC_MATCH_SRV_NAMEONLY 0x00000040
2303/** The second ticket must match. */
2304#define KRB5_TC_MATCH_2ND_TKT 0x00000080
2305/** The encryption key type must match. */
2306#define KRB5_TC_MATCH_KTYPE 0x00000100
2307/** The supported key types must match. */
2308#define KRB5_TC_SUPPORTED_KTYPES 0x00000200
2309
2310/* Flags for krb5_cc_set_flags and similar. */
2311/** Open and close the file for each cache operation. */
2312#define KRB5_TC_OPENCLOSE 0x00000001 /**< @deprecated has no effect */
2313#define KRB5_TC_NOTICKET 0x00000002

2423/**
2424 * Retrieve a specified credentials from a credential cache.
2425 *
2426 * @param [in] context Library context
2427 * @param [in] cache Credential cache handle
2428 * @param [in] flags Flags bit mask
2429 * @param [in] mcreds Credentials to match
2430 * @param [out] creds Credentials matching the requested value
2431 *
2432 * This function searches a credential cache for credentials matching @a mcreds
2433 * and returns it if found.
2434 *
2435 * Valid values for @a flags are:
2436 *
2437 * @li #KRB5_TC_MATCH_TIMES The requested lifetime must be at least as
2438 * great as in @a mcreds .
2439 * @li #KRB5_TC_MATCH_IS_SKEY The @a is_skey field much match exactly.
2440 * @li #KRB5_TC_MATCH_FLAGS Flags set in @a mcreds must be set.
2441 * @li #KRB5_TC_MATCH_TIMES_EXACT The requested lifetime must match exactly.
2442 * @li #KRB5_TC_MATCH_FLAGS_EXACT Flags must match exactly.
2443 * @li #KRB5_TC_MATCH_AUTHDATA The authorization data must match.
2444 * @li #KRB5_TC_MATCH_SRV_NAMEONLY Only the name portion of the principal
2445 * name must match, not the realm.
2446 * @li #KRB5_TC_MATCH_2ND_TKT The second tickets must match.
2447 * @li #KRB5_TC_MATCH_KTYPE The encryption key types must match.
2448 * @li #KRB5_TC_SUPPORTED_KTYPES Check all matching entries that have any
2449 * supported encryption type and return the
2450 * one with the encryption type listed earliest.
2451 *
2452 * Use krb5_free_cred_contents() to free @a creds when it is no longer needed.
2453 *
2454 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
2455 */
2456krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
2457krb5_cc_retrieve_cred(krb5_context context, krb5_ccache cache,
2458 krb5_flags flags, krb5_creds *mcreds,
2459 krb5_creds *creds);

2813 krb5_kvno vno; /**< Key version number */

2867/**
2868 * Get an entry from a key table.
2869 *
2870 * @param [in] context Library context
2871 * @param [in] keytab Key table handle
2872 * @param [in] principal Principal name
2873 * @param [in] vno Key version number (0 for highest available)
2874 * @param [in] enctype Encryption type (0 zero for any enctype)
2875 * @param [out] entry Returned entry from key table
2876 *
2877 * Retrieve an entry from a key table which matches the @a keytab, @a
2878 * principal, @a vno, and @a enctype. If @a vno is zero, retrieve the
2879 * highest-numbered kvno matching the other fields. If @a enctype is 0, match
2880 * any enctype.
2881 *
2882 * Use krb5_free_keytab_entry_contents() to free @a entry when it is no longer
2883 * needed.
2884 *
2885 * @note If @a vno is zero, the function retrieves the highest-numbered-kvno
2886 * entry that matches the specified principal.
2887 *
2888 * @retval
2889 * 0 Success
2890 * @retval
2891 * Kerberos error codes on failure
2892 */
2893krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
2894krb5_kt_get_entry(krb5_context context, krb5_keytab keytab,
2895 krb5_const_principal principal, krb5_kvno vno,
2896 krb5_enctype enctype, krb5_keytab_entry *entry);
2897
2898/**
2899 * Start a sequential retrieval of key table entries.
2900 *
2901 * @param [in] context Library context
2902 * @param [in] keytab Key table handle
2903 * @param [out] cursor Cursor
2904 *
2905 * Prepare to read sequentially every key in the specified key table. Use
2906 * krb5_kt_end_seq_get() to release the cursor when it is no longer needed.
2907 *
2908 * @sa krb5_kt_next_entry(), krb5_kt_end_seq_get()

2910 * @retval
2911 * 0 Success
2912 * @return
2913 * Kerberos error codes
2914 */

2916krb5_kt_start_seq_get(krb5_context context, krb5_keytab keytab,
2917 krb5_kt_cursor *cursor);

2925 * @param [in] cursor Key table cursor
2926 *

2928 * Callers must release the returned entry with krb5_kt_free_entry().
2929 *

2933 * 0 Success

2936 * @return
2937 * Kerberos error codes
2938 */

2952 *

3155#define KRB5_GC_CANONICALIZE 4 /**< Set canonicalize KDC option */
3156#define KRB5_GC_NO_STORE 8 /**< Do not store in credential cache */

3162/**
3163 * Get an additional ticket.
3164 *
3165 * @param [in] context Library context
3166 * @param [in] options Options
3167 * @param [in] ccache Credential cache handle
3168 * @param [in] in_creds Input credentials
3169 * @param [out] out_creds Output updated credentials
3170 *
3171 * Use @a ccache or a TGS exchange to get a service ticket matching @a
3172 * in_creds.
3173 *
3174 * Valid values for @a options are:
3175 * @li #KRB5_GC_CACHED Search only credential cache for the ticket
3176 * @li #KRB5_GC_USER_USER Return a user to user authentication ticket
3177 *
3178 * @a in_creds must be non-null. @a in_creds->client and @a in_creds->server
3179 * must be filled in to specify the client and the server respectively. If any
3180 * authorization data needs to be requested for the service ticket (such as
3181 * restrictions on how the ticket can be used), specify it in @a
3182 * in_creds->authdata; otherwise set @a in_creds->authdata to NULL. The
3183 * session key type is specified in @a in_creds->keyblock.enctype, if it is
3184 * nonzero.
3185 *
3186 * The expiration date is specified in @a in_creds->times.endtime.
3187 * The KDC may return tickets with an earlier expiration date.
3188 * If @a in_creds->times.endtime is set to 0, the latest possible
3189 * expiration date will be requested.
3190 *
3191 * Any returned ticket and intermediate ticket-granting tickets are stored
3192 * in @a ccache.
3193 *
3194 * Use krb5_free_creds() to free @a out_creds when it is no longer needed.
3195 *
3196 * @retval
3197 * 0 Success
3198 * @return
3199 * Kerberos error codes
3200 */
3201krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
3202krb5_get_credentials(krb5_context context, krb5_flags options,
3203 krb5_ccache ccache, krb5_creds *in_creds,
3204 krb5_creds **out_creds);
3205
3206/** @deprecated Replaced by krb5_get_validated_creds. */
3207krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
3208krb5_get_credentials_validate(krb5_context context, krb5_flags options,
3209 krb5_ccache ccache, krb5_creds *in_creds,
3210 krb5_creds **out_creds);
3211
3212/** @deprecated Replaced by krb5_get_renewed_creds. */
3213krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
3214krb5_get_credentials_renew(krb5_context context, krb5_flags options,

3216 krb5_creds **out_creds);

3218/**
3219 * Create a @c KRB_AP_REQ message.
3220 *
3221 * @param [in] context Library context
3222 * @param [in,out] auth_context Pre-existing or newly created auth context
3223 * @param [in] ap_req_options @ref AP_OPTS options
3224 * @param [in] service Service name, or NULL to use @c "host"
3225 * @param [in] hostname Host name, or NULL to use local hostname
3226 * @param [in] in_data Application data to be checksummed in the
3227 * authenticator, or NULL
3228 * @param [in] ccache Credential cache used to obtain credentials
3229 * for the desired service.
3230 * @param [out] outbuf @c AP-REQ message
3231 *
3232 * This function is similar to krb5_mk_req_extended() except that it uses a
3233 * given @a hostname, @a service, and @a ccache to construct a service
3234 * principal name and obtain credentials.
3235 *
3236 * Use krb5_free_data_contents() to free @a outbuf when it is no longer needed.
3237 *
3238 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
3239 */
3240krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
3241krb5_mk_req(krb5_context context, krb5_auth_context *auth_context,
3242 krb5_flags ap_req_options, char *service, char *hostname,
3243 krb5_data *in_data, krb5_ccache ccache, krb5_data *outbuf);
3244
3245/**
3246 * Create a @c KRB_AP_REQ message using supplied credentials.
3247 *
3248 * @param [in] context Library context
3249 * @param [in,out] auth_context Pre-existing or newly created auth context
3250 * @param [in] ap_req_options @ref AP_OPTS options
3251 * @param [in] in_data Application data to be checksummed in the
3252 * authenticator, or NULL
3253 * @param [in] in_creds Credentials for the service with valid ticket
3254 * and key
3255 * @param [out] outbuf @c AP-REQ message
3256 *
3257 * Valid @a ap_req_options are:
3258 * @li #AP_OPTS_USE_SESSION_KEY - Use the session key when creating the
3259 * request used for user to user
3260 * authentication.
3261 * @li #AP_OPTS_MUTUAL_REQUIRED - Request a mutual authentication packet from
3262 * the reciever.
3263 * @li #AP_OPTS_USE_SUBKEY - Generate a subsession key from the current
3264 * session key obtained from the credentials.
3265 *
3266 * This function creates a KRB_AP_REQ message using supplied credentials @a
3267 * in_creds. @a auth_context may point to an existing auth context or to NULL,
3268 * in which case a new one will be created. If @a in_data is non-null, a
3269 * checksum of it will be included in the authenticator contained in the
3270 * KRB_AP_REQ message. Use krb5_free_data_contents() to free @a outbuf when it
3271 * is no longer needed.
3272 *
3273 * On successful return, the authenticator is stored in @a auth_context with
3274 * the @a client and @a checksum fields nulled out. (This is to prevent
3275 * pointer-sharing problems; the caller should not need these fields anyway,
3276 * since the caller supplied them.)
3277 *
3278 * @sa krb5_mk_req()
3279 *
3280 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
3281 */
3282krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
3283krb5_mk_req_extended(krb5_context context, krb5_auth_context *auth_context,
3284 krb5_flags ap_req_options, krb5_data *in_data,
3285 krb5_creds *in_creds, krb5_data *outbuf);
3286

3288 * Format and encrypt a @c KRB_AP_REP message.
3289 *
3290 * @param [in] context Library context
3291 * @param [in] auth_context Authentication context
3292 * @param [out] outbuf @c AP-REP message
3293 *
3294 * This function fills in @a outbuf with an AP-REP message using information
3295 * from @a auth_context.
3296 *
3297 * If the flags in @a auth_context indicate that a sequence number should be

3300 * auth_context is 0, a new number will be generated with
3301 * krb5_generate_seq_number().
3302 *
3303 * Use krb5_free_data_contents() to free @a outbuf when it is no longer needed.
3304 *
3305 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
3306 */
3307krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
3308krb5_mk_rep(krb5_context context, krb5_auth_context auth_context, krb5_data *outbuf);

3398 * @param [in] auth_context Authentication context
3399 * @param [in] inbuf @c KRB-SAFE message to be parsed
3400 * @param [out] outbuf Data parsed from @c KRB-SAFE message
3401 * @param [out] outdata Replay data. Specify NULL if not needed
3402 *
3403 * This function parses a @c KRB-SAFE message, verifies its integrity, and
3404 * stores its data into @a outbuf.
3405 *
3406 * @note The @a outdata argument is required if #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_RET_TIME or
3407 * #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_RET_SEQUENCE flag is set in the @a auth_context.
3408 *
3409 * @note @a auth_context must have a remote address set. This address will be
3410 * used to verify the sender address in the KRB-SAFE message. If @a
3411 * auth_context has a local address set, it will be used to verify the
3412 * receiver address in the KRB-SAFE message if the message contains one.
3413 * Both addresses must use type @c ADDRTYPE_ADDRPORT.
3414 *
3415 * If the #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_DO_SEQUENCE flag is set in @a auth_context, the
3416 * sequence number of the KRB-SAFE message is checked against the remote
3417 * sequence number field of @a auth_context. Otherwise, the sequence number is
3418 * not used.
3419 *
3420 * If the #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_DO_TIME flag is set in @a auth_context,
3421 * then two additional checks are performed:
3422 * @li The timestamp in the message must be within the permitted clock skew
3423 * (which is usually five minutes).
3424 * @li The message must not be a replayed message field in @a auth_context.
3425 *
3426 * Use krb5_free_data_contents() to free @a outbuf when it is no longer needed.
3427 *
3428 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
3429 */
3430krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
3431krb5_rd_safe(krb5_context context, krb5_auth_context auth_context,
3432 const krb5_data *inbuf, krb5_data *outbuf,
3433 krb5_replay_data *outdata);
3434
3435/**
3436 * Process a @c KRB-PRIV message.
3437 *
3438 * @param [in] context Library context
3439 * @param [in] auth_context Authentication structure
3440 * @param [in] inbuf @c KRB-PRIV message to be parsed
3441 * @param [out] outbuf Data parsed from @c KRB-PRIV message
3442 * @param [out] outdata Replay data. Specify NULL if not needed
3443 *
3444 * This function parses a @c KRB-PRIV message, verifies its integrity, and
3445 * stores its unencrypted data into @a outbuf.
3446 *
3447 * @note If the #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_RET_TIME or
3448 * #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_RET_SEQUENCE flag is set in @a auth_context, @a
3449 * outdata is required.
3450 *
3451 * @note @a auth_context must have a remote address set. This address will be
3452 * used to verify the sender address in the KRB-PRIV message. If @a
3453 * auth_context has a local address set, it will be used to verify the
3454 * receiver address in the KRB-PRIV message if the message contains one.
3455 * Both addresses must use type @c ADDRTYPE_ADDRPORT.
3456 *
3457 * If the #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_DO_SEQUENCE flag is set in @a auth_context, the
3458 * sequence number of the KRB-SAFE message is checked against the remote
3459 * sequence number field of @a auth_context. Otherwise, the sequence number is
3460 * not used.
3461 *
3462 * If the #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_DO_TIME flag is set in @a auth_context,
3463 * then two additional checks are performed:
3464 * @li The timestamp in the message must be within the permitted clock skew
3465 * (which is usually five minutes).
3466 * @li The message must not be a replayed message field in @a auth_context.
3467 *
3468 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
3469 */
3470krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
3471krb5_rd_priv(krb5_context context, krb5_auth_context auth_context,
3472 const krb5_data *inbuf, krb5_data *outbuf,
3473 krb5_replay_data *outdata);
3474
3475/**
3476 * Convert a string principal name to a krb5_principal structure.
3477 *
3478 * @param [in] context Library context
3479 * @param [in] name String representation of a principal name
3480 * @param [out] principal_out New principal
3481 *
3482 * Convert a string representation of a principal name to a krb5_principal
3483 * structure.
3484 *
3485 * A string representation of a Kerberos name consists of one or more principal
3486 * name components, separated by slashes, optionally followed by the \@
3487 * character and a realm name. If the realm name is not specified, the local
3488 * realm is used.
3489 *
3490 * To use the slash and \@ symbols as part of a component (quoted) instead of
3491 * using them as a component separator or as a realm prefix), put a backslash
3492 * (\) character in front of the symbol. Similarly, newline, tab, backspace,
3493 * and NULL characters can be included in a component by using @c n, @c t, @c b
3494 * or @c 0, respectively.
3495 *
3496 * @note The realm in a Kerberos @a name cannot contain slash, colon,
3497 * or NULL characters.
3498 *
3499 * Use krb5_free_principal() to free @a principal_out when it is no longer
3500 * needed.
3501 *
3502 * @retval
3503 * 0 Success
3504 * @return
3505 * Kerberos error codes
3506 */
3507krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
3508krb5_parse_name(krb5_context context, const char *name,
3509 krb5_principal *principal_out);
3510
3511#define KRB5_PRINCIPAL_PARSE_NO_REALM 0x1 /**< Error if realm is present */
3512#define KRB5_PRINCIPAL_PARSE_REQUIRE_REALM 0x2 /**< Error if realm is not present */
3513#define KRB5_PRINCIPAL_PARSE_ENTERPRISE 0x4 /**< Create single-component
3514 enterprise principle */
3515#define KRB5_PRINCIPAL_PARSE_IGNORE_REALM 0x8 /**< Ignore realm if present */
3516
3517/**
3518 * Convert a string principal name to a krb5_principal with flags.
3519 *
3520 * @param [in] context Library context
3521 * @param [in] name String representation of a principal name
3522 * @param [in] flags Flag
3523 * @param [out] principal_out New principal
3524 *
3525 * Similar to krb5_parse_name(), this function converts a single-string
3526 * representation of a principal name to a krb5_principal structure.
3527 *
3528 * The following flags are valid:
3529 * @li #KRB5_PRINCIPAL_PARSE_NO_REALM - no realm must be present in @a name
3530 * @li #KRB5_PRINCIPAL_PARSE_REQUIRE_REALM - realm must be present in @a name
3531 * @li #KRB5_PRINCIPAL_PARSE_ENTERPRISE - create single-component enterprise
3532 * principal
3533 * @li #KRB5_PRINCIPAL_PARSE_IGNORE_REALM - ignore realm if present in @a name
3534 *
3535 * If @c KRB5_PRINCIPAL_PARSE_NO_REALM or @c KRB5_PRINCIPAL_PARSE_IGNORE_REALM
3536 * is specified in @a flags, the realm of the new principal will be empty.
3537 * Otherwise, the default realm for @a context will be used if @a name does not
3538 * specify a realm.
3539 *
3540 * Use krb5_free_principal() to free @a principal_out when it is no longer
3541 * needed.
3542 *
3543 * @retval
3544 * 0 Success
3545 * @return
3546 * Kerberos error codes
3547 */
3548krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
3549krb5_parse_name_flags(krb5_context context, const char *name,
3550 int flags, krb5_principal *principal_out);
3551
3552/**
3553 * Convert a krb5_principal structure to a string representation.
3554 *
3555 * @param [in] context Library context
3556 * @param [in] principal Principal
3557 * @param [out] name String representation of principal name
3558 *
3559 * The resulting string representation uses the format and quoting conventions
3560 * described for krb5_parse_name().
3561 *
3562 * Use krb5_free_unparsed_name() to free @a name when it is no longer needed.
3563 *
3564 * @retval
3565 * 0 Success
3566 * @return
3567 * Kerberos error codes
3568 */
3569krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
3570krb5_unparse_name(krb5_context context, krb5_const_principal principal,
3571 register char **name);
3572
3573/**
3574 * Convert krb5_principal structure to string and length.
3575 *
3576 * @param [in] context Library context
3577 * @param [in] principal Principal
3578 * @param [in,out] name String representation of principal name
3579 * @param [in,out] size Size of unparsed name
3580 *
3581 * This function is similar to krb5_unparse_name(), but allows the use of an
3582 * existing buffer for the result. If size is not NULL, then @a name must
3583 * point to either NULL or an existing buffer of at least the size pointed to
3584 * by @a size. The buffer will be allocated or resized if necessary, with the
3585 * new pointer stored into @a name. Whether or not the buffer is resized, the
3586 * necessary space for the result, including null terminator, will be stored
3587 * into @a size.
3588 *
3589 * If size is NULL, this function behaves exactly as krb5_unparse_name().
3590 *
3591 * @retval
3592 * 0 Success
3593 * @return
3594 * Kerberos error codes. On failure @a name is set to NULL
3595 */
3596krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
3597krb5_unparse_name_ext(krb5_context context, krb5_const_principal principal,
3598 char **name, unsigned int *size);
3599
3600#define KRB5_PRINCIPAL_UNPARSE_SHORT 0x1 /**< Omit realm if it is the local realm */
3601#define KRB5_PRINCIPAL_UNPARSE_NO_REALM 0x2 /**< Omit realm always */
3602#define KRB5_PRINCIPAL_UNPARSE_DISPLAY 0x4 /**< Don't escape special characters */

3615 * The following flags are valid:
3616 * @li #KRB5_PRINCIPAL_UNPARSE_SHORT - omit realm if it is the local realm
3617 * @li #KRB5_PRINCIPAL_UNPARSE_NO_REALM - omit realm

3623 * 0 Success

3974 * @param [in] inauthdat1 First list of @a krb5_authdata structures
3975 * @param [in] inauthdat2 Second list of @a krb5_authdata structures
3976 * @param [out] outauthdat Merged list of @a krb5_authdata structures

3979 * and authenticator.

3983 * must be a NULL pointer.
3984 *
3985 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
3986 */

3990 krb5_authdata * const *inauthdat2,

4045/**
4046 * Build a principal name using length-counted strings.
4047 *
4048 * @param [in] context Library context
4049 * @param [out] princ Principal name
4050 * @param [in] rlen Realm name length
4051 * @param [in] realm Realm name
4052 * @param [in] ... List of unsigned int/char * components, followed by 0
4053 *
4054 * This function creates a principal from a length-counted string and a
4055 * variable-length list of length-counted components. The list of components
4056 * ends with the first 0 length argument (so it is not possible to specify an
4057 * empty component with this function). Call krb5_free_principal() to free
4058 * allocated memory for principal when it is no longer needed.
4059 *
4060 * @code
4061 * Example of how to build principal WELLKNOWN/ANONYMOUS@R
4062 * krb5_build_principal_ext(context, &principal, strlen("R"), "R",
4063 * (unsigned int)strlen(KRB5_WELLKNOWN_NAMESTR),
4064 * KRB5_WELLKNOWN_NAMESTR,
4065 * (unsigned int)strlen(KRB5_ANONYMOUS_PRINCSTR),
4066 * KRB5_ANONYMOUS_PRINCSTR, 0);
4067 * @endcode
4068 *
4069 * @retval
4070 * 0 Success
4071 * @return
4072 * Kerberos error codes
4073 */
4074krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV_C
4075krb5_build_principal_ext(krb5_context context, krb5_principal * princ,
4076 unsigned int rlen, const char * realm, ...);

4084 * @param [in] realm Realm name

4088 *

4090 * same task. krb5_build_principal() takes variadic arguments.
4091 * krb5_build_principal_alloc_va() takes a pre-computed @a varargs pointer.
4092 *
4093 * @code

4096 * strlen("R"), "R", "H", "S", (char*)NULL);

4111#endif

4441 * Return a pointer to the default credential cache name for @a context, as
4442 * determined by a prior call to krb5_cc_set_default_name(), by the KRB5CCNAME
4443 * environment variable, by the default_ccache_name profile variable, or by the
4444 * operating system or build-time default value. The returned value must not
4445 * be modified or freed by the caller. The returned value becomes invalid when
4446 * @a context is destroyed krb5_free_context() or if a subsequent call to
4447 * krb5_cc_set_default_name() is made on @a context.
4448 *
4449 * The default credential cache name is cached in @a context between calls to
4450 * this function, so if the value of KRB5CCNAME changes in the process
4451 * environment after the first call to this function on, that change will not
4452 * be reflected in later calls with the same context. The caller can invoke
4453 * krb5_cc_set_default_name() with a NULL value of @a name to clear the cached
4454 * value and force the default name to be recomputed.
4455 *
4456 * @return
4457 * Name of default credential cache for the current user.
4458 */

4618 *
4619 * @retval 0 Success
4620 * @retval KRB5_CC_NOTFOUND
4621 *
4622 * @sa krb5_cccol_cursor_new
4623 *
4624 * @version New in 1.10
4625 */
4626krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
4627krb5_cc_cache_match(krb5_context context, krb5_principal client,
4628 krb5_ccache *cache_out);
4629
4630/**
4631 * Select a credential cache to use with a server principal.
4632 *
4633 * @param [in] context Library context
4634 * @param [in] server Server principal
4635 * @param [out] cache_out Credential cache handle
4636 * @param [out] princ_out Client principal
4637 *
4638 * Select a cache within the collection containing credentials most appropriate
4639 * for use with @a server, according to configured rules and heuristics.
4640 *
4641 * Use krb5_cc_close() to release @a cache_out when it is no longer needed.
4642 * Use krb5_free_principal() to release @a princ_out when it is no longer
4643 * needed. Note that @a princ_out is set in some error conditions.
4644 *
4645 * @return
4646 * If an appropriate cache is found, 0 is returned, @a cache_out is set to the
4647 * selected cache, and @a princ_out is set to the default principal of that
4648 * cache.
4649 *
4650 * If the appropriate client principal can be authoritatively determined but
4651 * the cache collection contains no credentials for that principal, then
4652 * KRB5_CC_NOTFOUND is returned, @a cache_out is set to NULL, and @a princ_out
4653 * is set to the appropriate client principal.
4654 *
4655 * If no configured mechanism can determine the appropriate cache or principal,
4656 * KRB5_CC_NOTFOUND is returned and @a cache_out and @a princ_out are set to
4657 * NULL.
4658 *
4659 * Any other error code indicates a fatal error in the processing of a cache
4660 * selection mechanism.
4661 *
4662 * @version New in 1.10
4663 */
4664krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
4665krb5_cc_select(krb5_context context, krb5_principal server,
4666 krb5_ccache *cache_out, krb5_principal *princ_out);

5011/**
5012 * Generate a full principal name from a service name.
5013 *
5014 * @param [in] context Library context
5015 * @param [in] hostname Host name, or NULL to use local host
5016 * @param [in] sname Service name, or NULL to use @c "host"
5017 * @param [in] type Principal type
5018 * @param [out] ret_princ Generated principal
5019 *
5020 * This function converts a @a hostname and @a sname into @a krb5_principal
5021 * structure @a ret_princ. The returned principal will be of the form @a
5022 * sname\/hostname\@REALM where REALM is determined by krb5_get_host_realm().
5023 * In some cases this may be the referral (empty) realm.
5024 *
5025 * The @a type can be one of the following:
5026 *
5027 * @li #KRB5_NT_SRV_HST canonicalizes the host name before looking up the
5028 * realm and generating the principal.
5029 *
5030 * @li #KRB5_NT_UNKNOWN accepts the hostname as given, and does not
5031 * canonicalize it.
5032 *
5033 * Use krb5_free_principal to free @a ret_princ when it is no longer needed.
5034 *
5035 * @retval
5036 * 0 Success
5037 * @return
5038 * Kerberos error codes
5039 */
5040krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
5041krb5_sname_to_principal(krb5_context context, const char *hostname, const char *sname,
5042 krb5_int32 type, krb5_principal *ret_princ);
5043
5044/**
5045 * Test whether a principal matches a matching principal.
5046 *
5047 * @param [in] context Library context
5048 * @param [in] matching Matching principal
5049 * @param [in] princ Principal to test
5050 *
5051 * @note A matching principal is a host-based principal with an empty realm
5052 * and/or second data component (hostname). Profile configuration may cause
5053 * the hostname to be ignored even if it is present. A principal matches a
5054 * matching principal if the former has the same non-empty (and non-ignored)
5055 * components of the latter.
5056 *
5057 * If @a matching is NULL, return TRUE. If @a matching is not a matching
5058 * principal, return the value of krb5_principal_compare(context, matching,
5059 * princ).
5060 *
5061 * @return
5062 * TRUE if @a princ matches @a matching, FALSE otherwise.
5063 */
5064krb5_boolean KRB5_CALLCONV
5065krb5_sname_match(krb5_context context, krb5_const_principal matching,
5066 krb5_const_principal princ);

5068/**
5069 * Change a password for an existing Kerberos account.
5070 *
5071 * @param [in] context Library context
5072 * @param [in] creds Credentials for kadmin/changepw service
5073 * @param [in] newpw New password
5074 * @param [out] result_code Numeric error code from server
5075 * @param [out] result_code_string String equivalent to @a result_code
5076 * @param [out] result_string Change password response from the KDC
5077 *
5078 * Change the password for the existing principal identified by @a creds.
5079 *
5080 * The possible values of the output @a result_code are:
5081 *
5082 * @li #KRB5_KPASSWD_SUCCESS (0) - success
5083 * @li #KRB5_KPASSWD_MALFORMED (1) - Malformed request error
5084 * @li #KRB5_KPASSWD_HARDERROR (2) - Server error
5085 * @li #KRB5_KPASSWD_AUTHERROR (3) - Authentication error
5086 * @li #KRB5_KPASSWD_SOFTERROR (4) - Password change rejected
5087 *
5088 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
5089 */
5090krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
5091krb5_change_password(krb5_context context, krb5_creds *creds,
5092 const char *newpw, int *result_code,
5093 krb5_data *result_code_string, krb5_data *result_string);
5094
5095/**
5096 * Set a password for a principal using specified credentials.
5097 *
5098 * @param [in] context Library context
5099 * @param [in] creds Credentials for kadmin/changepw service
5100 * @param [in] newpw New password
5101 * @param [in] change_password_for Change the password for this principal
5102 * @param [out] result_code Numeric error code from server
5103 * @param [out] result_code_string String equivalent to @a result_code
5104 * @param [out] result_string Data returned from the remote system
5105 *
5106 * This function uses the credentials @a creds to set the password @a newpw for
5107 * the principal @a change_password_for. It implements the set password
5108 * operation of RFC 3244, for interoperability with Microsoft Windows
5109 * implementations.
5110 *
5111 * @note If @a change_password_for is NULL, the change is performed on the
5112 * current principal. If @a change_password_for is non-null, the change is
5113 * performed on the principal name passed in @a change_password_for.
5114 *
5115 * The error code and strings are returned in @a result_code,
5116 * @a result_code_string and @a result_string.
5117 *
5118 * @sa krb5_set_password_using_ccache()
5119 *
5120 * @retval
5121 * 0 Success and result_code is set to #KRB5_KPASSWD_SUCCESS.
5122 * @return
5123 * Kerberos error codes.
5124 */
5125krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
5126krb5_set_password(krb5_context context, krb5_creds *creds, const char *newpw,
5127 krb5_principal change_password_for, int *result_code,
5128 krb5_data *result_code_string, krb5_data *result_string);
5129
5130/**
5131 * Set a password for a principal using cached credentials.
5132 *
5133 * @param [in] context Library context
5134 * @param [in] ccache Credential cache
5135 * @param [in] newpw New password
5136 * @param [in] change_password_for Change the password for this principal
5137 * @param [out] result_code Numeric error code from server
5138 * @param [out] result_code_string String equivalent to @a result_code
5139 * @param [out] result_string Data returned from the remote system
5140 *
5141 * This function uses the cached credentials from @a ccache to set the password
5142 * @a newpw for the principal @a change_password_for. It implements RFC 3244
5143 * set password operation (interoperable with MS Windows implementations) using
5144 * the credential cache.
5145 *
5146 * The error code and strings are returned in @a result_code,
5147 * @a result_code_string and @a result_string.
5148 *
5149 * @note If @a change_password_for is set to NULL, the change is performed on
5150 * the default principal in @a ccache. If @a change_password_for is non null,
5151 * the change is performed on the specified principal.
5152 *
5153 * @sa krb5_set_password()
5154 *
5155 * @retval
5156 * 0 Success
5157 * @return
5158 * Kerberos error codes
5159 */
5160krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
5161krb5_set_password_using_ccache(krb5_context context, krb5_ccache ccache,
5162 const char *newpw,
5163 krb5_principal change_password_for,
5164 int *result_code, krb5_data *result_code_string,
5165 krb5_data *result_string);
5166
5167/**
5168 * Get a result message for changing or setting a password.
5169 *
5170 * @param [in] context Library context
5171 * @param [in] server_string Data returned from the remote system
5172 * @param [out] message_out A message displayable to the user
5173 *
5174 * This function processes the @a server_string returned in the @a
5175 * result_string parameter of krb5_change_password(), krb5_set_password(), and
5176 * related functions, and returns a displayable string. If @a server_string
5177 * contains Active Directory structured policy information, it will be
5178 * converted into human-readable text.
5179 *
5180 * Use krb5_free_string() to free @a message_out when it is no longer needed.
5181 *
5182 * @retval
5183 * 0 Success
5184 * @return
5185 * Kerberos error codes
5186 *
5187 * @version New in 1.11
5188 */
5189krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
5190krb5_chpw_message(krb5_context context, const krb5_data *server_string,

5238#endif /* KRB5_DEPRECATED */
5239
5240/**
5241 * Parse and decrypt a @c KRB_AP_REQ message.
5242 *
5243 * @param [in] context Library context
5244 * @param [in,out] auth_context Pre-existing or newly created auth context
5245 * @param [in] inbuf AP-REQ message to be parsed
5246 * @param [in] server Matching principal for server, or NULL to
5247 * allow any principal in keytab
5248 * @param [in] keytab Key table, or NULL to use the default
5249 * @param [out] ap_req_options If non-null, the AP-REQ flags on output
5250 * @param [out] ticket If non-null, ticket from the AP-REQ message
5251 *
5252 * This function parses, decrypts and verifies a AP-REQ message from @a inbuf
5253 * and stores the authenticator in @a auth_context.
5254 *
5255 * If a keyblock was specified in @a auth_context using
5256 * krb5_auth_con_setuseruserkey(), that key is used to decrypt the ticket in
5257 * AP-REQ message and @a keytab is ignored. In this case, @a server should be
5258 * specified as a complete principal name to allow for proper transited-path
5259 * checking and replay cache selection.
5260 *
5261 * Otherwise, the decryption key is obtained from @a keytab, or from the
5262 * default keytab if it is NULL. In this case, @a server may be a complete
5263 * principal name, a matching principal (see krb5_sname_match()), or NULL to
5264 * match any principal name. The keys tried against the encrypted part of the
5265 * ticket are determined as follows:
5266 *
5267 * - If @a server is a complete principal name, then its entry in @a keytab is
5268 * tried.
5269 * - Otherwise, if @a keytab is iterable, then all entries in @a keytab which
5270 * match @a server are tried.
5271 * - Otherwise, the server principal in the ticket must match @a server, and
5272 * its entry in @a keytab is tried.
5273 *
5274 * The client specified in the decrypted authenticator must match the client
5275 * specified in the decrypted ticket.
5276 *
5277 * If the @a remote_addr field of @a auth_context is set, the request must come
5278 * from that address.
5279 *
5280 * If a replay cache handle is provided in the @a auth_context, the
5281 * authenticator and ticket are verified against it. If no conflict is found,
5282 * the new authenticator is then stored in the replay cache of @a auth_context.
5283 *
5284 * Various other checks are performed on the decoded data, including
5285 * cross-realm policy, clockskew, and ticket validation times.
5286 *
5287 * On success the authenticator, subkey, and remote sequence number of the
5288 * request are stored in @a auth_context. If the #AP_OPTS_MUTUAL_REQUIRED
5289 * bit is set, the local sequence number is XORed with the remote sequence
5290 * number in the request.
5291 *
5292 * Use krb5_free_ticket() to free @a ticket when it is no longer needed.
5293 *
5294 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
5295 */
5296krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
5297krb5_rd_req(krb5_context context, krb5_auth_context *auth_context,
5298 const krb5_data *inbuf, krb5_const_principal server,
5299 krb5_keytab keytab, krb5_flags *ap_req_options,
5300 krb5_ticket **ticket);
5301
5302/**
5303 * Retrieve a service key from a key table.
5304 *
5305 * @param [in] context Library context
5306 * @param [in] keyprocarg Name of a key table (NULL to use default name)
5307 * @param [in] principal Service principal
5308 * @param [in] vno Key version number (0 for highest available)
5309 * @param [in] enctype Encryption type (0 for any type)
5310 * @param [out] key Service key from key table
5311 *
5312 * Open and search the specified key table for the entry identified by @a
5313 * principal, @a enctype, and @a vno. If no key is found, return an error code.
5314 *
5315 * The default key table is used, unless @a keyprocarg is non-null.
5316 * @a keyprocarg designates a specific key table.
5317 *
5318 * Use krb5_free_keyblock() to free @a key when it is no longer needed.
5319 *
5320 * @retval
5321 * 0 Success
5322 * @return Kerberos error code if not found or @a keyprocarg is invalid.
5323 */
5324krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
5325krb5_kt_read_service_key(krb5_context context, krb5_pointer keyprocarg,
5326 krb5_principal principal, krb5_kvno vno,
5327 krb5_enctype enctype, krb5_keyblock **key);
5328
5329/**
5330 * Format a @c KRB-SAFE message.
5331 *
5332 * @param [in] context Library context
5333 * @param [in] auth_context Authentication context
5334 * @param [in] userdata User data in the message
5335 * @param [out] outbuf Formatted @c KRB-SAFE buffer
5336 * @param [out] outdata Replay data. Specify NULL if not needed
5337 *
5338 * This function creates an integrity protected @c KRB-SAFE message
5339 * using data supplied by the application.
5340 *
5341 * Fields in @a auth_context specify the checksum type, the keyblock that
5342 * can be used to seed the checksum, full addresses (host and port) for
5343 * the sender and receiver, and @ref KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT flags.
5344 *
5345 * The local address in @a auth_context must be set, and is used to form the
5346 * sender address used in the KRB-SAFE message. The remote address is
5347 * optional; if specified, it will be used to form the receiver address used in
5348 * the message.
5349 *
5350 * If #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_DO_TIME flag is set in the @a auth_context, an entry
5351 * describing the message is entered in the replay cache @a
5352 * auth_context->rcache which enables the caller to detect if this message is
5353 * reflected by an attacker. If #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_DO_TIME is not set, the
5354 * replay cache is not used.
5355 *
5356 * If either #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_DO_SEQUENCE or
5357 * #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_RET_SEQUENCE is set, the @a auth_context local sequence
5358 * number will be placed in @a outdata as its sequence number.
5359 *
5360 * @note The @a outdata argument is required if #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_RET_TIME or
5361 * #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_RET_SEQUENCE flag is set in the @a auth_context.
5362 *
5363 * Use krb5_free_data_contents() to free @a outbuf when it is no longer needed.
5364 *
5365 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
5366 */
5367krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
5368krb5_mk_safe(krb5_context context, krb5_auth_context auth_context,
5369 const krb5_data *userdata, krb5_data *outbuf,
5370 krb5_replay_data *outdata);
5371
5372/**
5373 * Format a @c KRB-PRIV message.
5374 *
5375 * @param [in] context Library context
5376 * @param [in] auth_context Authentication context
5377 * @param [in] userdata User data for @c KRB-PRIV message
5378 * @param [out] outbuf Formatted @c KRB-PRIV message
5379 * @param [out] outdata Replay cache handle (NULL if not needed)
5380 *
5381 * This function is similar to krb5_mk_safe(), but the message is encrypted and
5382 * integrity-protected, not just integrity-protected.
5383 *
5384 * The local address in @a auth_context must be set, and is used to form the
5385 * sender address used in the KRB-SAFE message. The remote address is
5386 * optional; if specified, it will be used to form the receiver address used in
5387 * the message.
5388 *
5389 * @note If the #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_RET_TIME or
5390 * #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_RET_SEQUENCE flag is set in @a auth_context, the @a
5391 * outdata is required.
5392 *
5393 * @note The flags from @a auth_context specify whether sequence numbers or
5394 * timestamps will be used to identify the message. Valid values are:
5395 *
5396 * @li #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_DO_TIME - Use timestamps in @a outdata
5397 * @li #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_RET_TIME - Copy timestamp to @a outdata.
5398 * @li #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_DO_SEQUENCE - Use local sequence numbers from
5399 * @a auth_context in replay cache.
5400 * @li #KRB5_AUTH_CONTEXT_RET_SEQUENCE - Use local sequence numbers from
5401 * @a auth_context as a sequence number
5402 * in the encrypted message @a outbuf.
5403 *
5404 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
5405 */
5406krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
5407krb5_mk_priv(krb5_context context, krb5_auth_context auth_context,
5408 const krb5_data *userdata, krb5_data *outbuf,
5409 krb5_replay_data *outdata);
5410
5411/**
5412 * Client function for @c sendauth protocol.
5413 *
5414 * @param [in] context Library context
5415 * @param [in,out] auth_context Pre-existing or newly created auth context
5416 * @param [in] fd File descriptor that describes network socket
5417 * @param [in] appl_version Application protocol version to be matched
5418 * with the receiver's application version
5419 * @param [in] client Client principal
5420 * @param [in] server Server principal
5421 * @param [in] ap_req_options @ref AP_OPTS options
5422 * @param [in] in_data Data to be sent to the server
5423 * @param [in] in_creds Input credentials, or NULL to use @a ccache
5424 * @param [in] ccache Credential cache
5425 * @param [out] error If non-null, contains KRB_ERROR message
5426 * returned from server
5427 * @param [out] rep_result If non-null and @a ap_req_options is
5428 * #AP_OPTS_MUTUAL_REQUIRED, contains the result
5429 * of mutual authentication exchange
5430 * @param [out] out_creds If non-null, the retrieved credentials
5431 *
5432 * This function performs the client side of a sendauth/recvauth exchange by
5433 * sending and receiving messages over @a fd.
5434 *
5435 * Credentials may be specified in three ways:
5436 *
5437 * @li If @a in_creds is NULL, credentials are obtained with
5438 * krb5_get_credentials() using the principals @a client and @a server. @a
5439 * server must be non-null; @a client may NULL to use the default principal of
5440 * @a ccache.
5441 *
5442 * @li If @a in_creds is non-null, but does not contain a ticket, credentials
5443 * for the exchange are obtained with krb5_get_credentials() using @a in_creds.
5444 * In this case, the values of @a client and @a server are unused.
5445 *
5446 * @li If @a in_creds is a complete credentials structure, it used directly.
5447 * In this case, the values of @a client, @a server, and @a ccache are unused.
5448 *
5449 * If the server is using a different application protocol than that specified
5450 * in @a appl_version, an error will be returned.
5451 *
5452 * Use krb5_free_creds() to free @a out_creds, krb5_free_ap_rep_enc_part() to
5453 * free @a rep_result, and krb5_free_error() to free @a error when they are no
5454 * longer needed.
5455 *
5456 * @sa krb5_recvauth()
5457 *
5458 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
5459 */
5460krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
5461krb5_sendauth(krb5_context context, krb5_auth_context *auth_context,
5462 krb5_pointer fd, char *appl_version, krb5_principal client,
5463 krb5_principal server, krb5_flags ap_req_options,
5464 krb5_data *in_data, krb5_creds *in_creds, krb5_ccache ccache,
5465 krb5_error **error, krb5_ap_rep_enc_part **rep_result,
5466 krb5_creds **out_creds);
5467

5469 * Server function for @a sendauth protocol.

5471 * @param [in] context Library context
5472 * @param [in,out] auth_context Pre-existing or newly created auth context
5473 * @param [in] fd File descriptor
5474 * @param [in] appl_version Application protocol version to be matched
5475 * against the client's application version
5476 * @param [in] server Server principal (NULL for any in @a keytab)
5477 * @param [in] flags Additional specifications
5478 * @param [in] keytab Key table containing service keys
5479 * @param [out] ticket Ticket (NULL if not needed)
5480 *
5481 * This function performs the server side of a sendauth/recvauth exchange by
5482 * sending and receiving messages over @a fd.
5483 *
5484 * Use krb5_free_ticket() to free @a ticket when it is no longer needed.
5485 *

5489 */
5490krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
5491krb5_recvauth(krb5_context context, krb5_auth_context *auth_context,
