6106/**
6107 * @brief Read a password from keyboard input.
6108 *
6109 * @param [in] context Library context
6110 * @param [in] prompt First user prompt when reading password
6111 * @param [in] prompt2 Second user prompt (NULL to prompt only once)
6112 * @param [out] return_pwd Returned password
6113 * @param [in,out] size_return On input, maximum size of password; on output,
6114 * size of password read
6115 *
6116 * This function reads a password from keyboard input and stores it in @a
6117 * return_pwd. @a size_return should be set by the caller to the amount of
6118 * storage space available in @a return_pwd; on successful return, it will be
6119 * set to the length of the password read.
6120 *
6121 * @a prompt is printed to the terminal, followed by ": ", and then a password
6122 * is read from the keyboard.
6123 *
6124 * If @a prompt2 is NULL, the password is read only once. Otherwise, @a
6125 * prompt2 is printed to the terminal and a second password is read. If the
6126 * two passwords entered are not identical, KRB5_LIBOS_BADPWDMATCH is returned.
6127 *
6128 * Echoing is turned off when the password is read.
6129 *
6130 * @retval
6131 * 0 Success
6132 * @return
6133 * Error in reading or verifying the password
6134 * @return
6135 * Kerberos error codes
6136 */
6137krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
6138krb5_read_password(krb5_context context,
6139 const char *prompt, const char *prompt2,
6140 char *return_pwd, unsigned int *size_return);
6141
6142/**
6143 * Convert a principal name to a local name.
6144 *
6145 * @param [in] context Library context
6146 * @param [in] aname Principal name
6147 * @param [in] lnsize_in Space available in @a lname
6148 * @param [out] lname Local name buffer to be filled in
6149 *
6150 * If @a aname does not correspond to any local account, KRB5_LNAME_NOTRANS is
6151 * returned. If @a lnsize_in is too small for the local name,
6152 * KRB5_CONFIG_NOTENUFSPACE is returned.
6153 *
6154 * Local names, rather than principal names, can be used by programs that
6155 * translate to an environment-specific name (for example, a user account
6156 * name).
6157 *
6158 * @retval
6159 * 0 Success
6160 * @retval
6161 * System errors
6162 * @return
6163 * Kerberos error codes
6164 */
6165krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
6166krb5_aname_to_localname(krb5_context context, krb5_const_principal aname,
6167 int lnsize_in, char *lname);

6169/**
6170 * Get the Kerberos realm names for a host.
6171 *
6172 * @param [in] context Library context
6173 * @param [in] host Host name (or NULL)
6174 * @param [out] realmsp Null-terminated list of realm names
6175 *
6176 * Fill in @a realmsp with a pointer to a null-terminated list of realm names.
6177 * If there are no known realms for the host, a list containing the referral
6178 * (empty) realm is returned.
6179 *
6180 * If @a host is NULL, the local host's realms are determined.
6181 *
6182 * Use krb5_free_host_realm() to release @a realmsp when it is no longer
6183 * needed.
6184 *
6185 * @retval
6186 * 0 Success
6187 * @retval
6188 * ENOMEM Insufficient memory
6189 * @return
6190 * Kerberos error codes
6191 */
6192krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
6193krb5_get_host_realm(krb5_context context, const char *host, char ***realmsp);
6194
6195/**
6196 *
6197 * @param [in] context Library context
6198 * @param [in] hdata Host name (or NULL)
6199 * @param [out] realmsp Null-terminated list of realm names
6200 *
6201 * Fill in @a realmsp with a pointer to a null-terminated list of realm names
6202 * obtained through heuristics or insecure resolution methods which have lower
6203 * priority than KDC referrals.
6204 *
6205 * If @a host is NULL, the local host's realms are determined.
6206 *
6207 * Use krb5_free_host_realm() to release @a realmsp when it is no longer
6208 * needed.
6209 */
6210krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
6211krb5_get_fallback_host_realm(krb5_context context,
6212 krb5_data *hdata, char ***realmsp);

6464/** Text for prompt used in prompter callback function. */
6465typedef struct _krb5_prompt {
6466 char *prompt; /**< The prompt to show to the user */
6467 int hidden; /**< Boolean; informative prompt or hidden (e.g. PIN) */
6468 krb5_data *reply; /**< Must be allocated before call to prompt routine */
6469} krb5_prompt;

6471/** Pointer to a prompter callback function. */

6473(KRB5_CALLCONV *krb5_prompter_fct)(krb5_context context, void *data,
6474 const char *name, const char *banner,
6475 int num_prompts, krb5_prompt prompts[]);

6477/**
6478 * Prompt user for password.
6479 *
6480 * @param [in] context Library context
6481 * @param data Unused (callback argument)
6482 * @param [in] name Name to output during prompt
6483 * @param [in] banner Banner to output during prompt
6484 * @param [in] num_prompts Number of prompts in @a prompts
6485 * @param [in] prompts Array of prompts and replies
6486 *
6487 * This function is intended to be used as a prompter callback for
6488 * krb5_get_init_creds_password() or krb5_init_creds_init().
6489 *
6490 * Writes @a name and @a banner to stdout, each followed by a newline, then
6491 * writes each prompt field in the @a prompts array, followed by ": ", and sets
6492 * the reply field of the entry to a line of input read from stdin. If the
6493 * hidden flag is set for a prompt, then terminal echoing is turned off when
6494 * input is read.
6495 *
6496 * @retval
6497 * 0 Success
6498 * @return
6499 * Kerberos error codes
6500 *
6501 */
6502krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
6503krb5_prompter_posix(krb5_context context, void *data, const char *name,
6504 const char *banner, int num_prompts,
6505 krb5_prompt prompts[]);
6506
6507/**
6508 * Long-term password responder question
6509 *
6510 * This question is asked when the long-term password is needed. It has no
6511 * challenge and the response is simply the password string.
6512 *
6513 * @version New in 1.11
6514 */
6515#define KRB5_RESPONDER_QUESTION_PASSWORD "password"
6516
6517/**
6518 * OTP responder question
6519 *
6520 * The OTP responder question is asked when the KDC indicates that an OTP
6521 * value is required in order to complete the authentication. The JSON format
6522 * of the challenge is:
6523 *
6524 * @n {
6525 * @n "service": <string (optional)>,
6526 * @n "tokenInfo": [
6527 * @n {
6528 * @n "flags": <number>,
6529 * @n "vendor": <string (optional)>,
6530 * @n "challenge": <string (optional)>,
6531 * @n "length": <number (optional)>,
6532 * @n "format": <number (optional)>,
6533 * @n "tokenID": <string (optional)>,
6534 * @n "algID": <string (optional)>,
6535 * @n },
6536 * @n ...
6537 * @n ]
6538 * @n }
6539 *
6540 * The answer to the question MUST be JSON formatted:
6541 *
6542 * @n {
6543 * @n "tokeninfo": <number>,
6544 * @n "value": <string (optional)>,
6545 * @n "pin": <string (optional)>,
6546 * @n }
6547 *
6548 * For more detail, please see RFC 6560.
6549 *
6550 * @version New in 1.11
6551 */
6552#define KRB5_RESPONDER_QUESTION_OTP "otp"
6553
6554/**
6555 * These format constants identify the format of the token value.
6556 */
6557#define KRB5_RESPONDER_OTP_FORMAT_DECIMAL 0
6558#define KRB5_RESPONDER_OTP_FORMAT_HEXADECIMAL 1
6559#define KRB5_RESPONDER_OTP_FORMAT_ALPHANUMERIC 2
6560
6561/**
6562 * This flag indicates that the token value MUST be collected.
6563 */
6564#define KRB5_RESPONDER_OTP_FLAGS_COLLECT_TOKEN 0x0001
6565
6566/**
6567 * This flag indicates that the PIN value MUST be collected.
6568 */
6569#define KRB5_RESPONDER_OTP_FLAGS_COLLECT_PIN 0x0002
6570
6571/**
6572 * This flag indicates that the token is now in re-synchronization mode with
6573 * the server. The user is expected to reply with the next code displayed on
6574 * the token.
6575 */
6576#define KRB5_RESPONDER_OTP_FLAGS_NEXTOTP 0x0004
6577
6578/**
6579 * This flag indicates that the PIN MUST be returned as a separate item. This
6580 * flag only takes effect if KRB5_RESPONDER_OTP_FLAGS_COLLECT_PIN is set. If
6581 * this flag is not set, the responder may either concatenate PIN + token value
6582 * and store it as "value" in the answer or it may return them separately. If
6583 * they are returned separately, they will be concatenated internally.
6584 */
6585#define KRB5_RESPONDER_OTP_FLAGS_SEPARATE_PIN 0x0008
6586
6587/**
6588 * PKINIT responder question
6589 *
6590 * The PKINIT responder question is asked when the client needs a password
6591 * that's being used to protect key information, and is formatted as a JSON
6592 * object. A specific identity's flags value, if not zero, is the bitwise-OR
6593 * of one or more of the KRB5_RESPONDER_PKINIT_FLAGS_TOKEN_* flags defined
6594 * below, and possibly other flags to be added later. Any resemblance to
6595 * similarly-named CKF_* values in the PKCS#11 API should not be depended on.
6596 *
6597 * @n {
6598 * @n identity <string> : flags <number>,
6599 * @n ...
6600 * @n }
6601 *
6602 * The answer to the question MUST be JSON formatted:
6603 *
6604 * @n {
6605 * @n identity <string> : password <string>,
6606 * @n ...
6607 * @n }
6608 *
6609 * @version New in 1.12
6610 */
6611#define KRB5_RESPONDER_QUESTION_PKINIT "pkinit"
6612
6613/**
6614 * This flag indicates that an incorrect PIN was supplied at least once since
6615 * the last time the correct PIN was supplied.
6616 */
6617#define KRB5_RESPONDER_PKINIT_FLAGS_TOKEN_USER_PIN_COUNT_LOW (1 << 0)
6618
6619/**
6620 * This flag indicates that supplying an incorrect PIN will cause the token to
6621 * lock itself.
6622 */
6623#define KRB5_RESPONDER_PKINIT_FLAGS_TOKEN_USER_PIN_FINAL_TRY (1 << 1)
6624
6625/**
6626 * This flag indicates that the user PIN is locked, and you can't log in to the
6627 * token with it.
6628 */
6629#define KRB5_RESPONDER_PKINIT_FLAGS_TOKEN_USER_PIN_LOCKED (1 << 2)
6630
6631/**
6632 * A container for a set of preauthentication questions and answers
6633 *
6634 * A responder context is supplied by the krb5 authentication system to a @ref
6635 * krb5_responder_fn callback. It contains a list of questions and can receive
6636 * answers. Questions contained in a responder context can be listed using
6637 * krb5_responder_list_questions(), retrieved using
6638 * krb5_responder_get_challenge(), or answered using
6639 * krb5_responder_set_answer(). The form of a question's challenge and
6640 * answer depend on the question name.
6641 *
6642 * @version New in 1.11
6643 */
6644typedef struct krb5_responder_context_st *krb5_responder_context;
6645
6646/**
6647 * List the question names contained in the responder context.
6648 *
6649 * @param [in] ctx Library context
6650 * @param [in] rctx Responder context
6651 *
6652 * Return a pointer to a null-terminated list of question names which are
6653 * present in @a rctx. The pointer is an alias, valid only as long as the
6654 * lifetime of @a rctx, and should not be modified or freed by the caller. A
6655 * question's challenge can be retrieved using krb5_responder_get_challenge()
6656 * and answered using krb5_responder_set_answer().
6657 *
6658 * @version New in 1.11
6659 */
6660const char * const * KRB5_CALLCONV
6661krb5_responder_list_questions(krb5_context ctx, krb5_responder_context rctx);
6662
6663/**
6664 * Retrieve the challenge data for a given question in the responder context.
6665 *
6666 * @param [in] ctx Library context
6667 * @param [in] rctx Responder context
6668 * @param [in] question Question name
6669 *
6670 * Return a pointer to a C string containing the challenge for @a question
6671 * within @a rctx, or NULL if the question is not present in @a rctx. The
6672 * structure of the question depends on the question name, but will always be
6673 * printable UTF-8 text. The returned pointer is an alias, valid only as long
6674 * as the lifetime of @a rctx, and should not be modified or freed by the
6675 * caller.
6676 *
6677 * @version New in 1.11
6678 */
6679const char * KRB5_CALLCONV
6680krb5_responder_get_challenge(krb5_context ctx, krb5_responder_context rctx,
6681 const char *question);
6682
6683/**
6684 * Answer a named question in the responder context.
6685 *
6686 * @param [in] ctx Library context
6687 * @param [in] rctx Responder context
6688 * @param [in] question Question name
6689 * @param [in] answer The string to set (MUST be printable UTF-8)
6690 *
6691 * This function supplies an answer to @a question within @a rctx. The
6692 * appropriate form of the answer depends on the question name.
6693 *
6694 * @retval EINVAL @a question is not present within @a rctx
6695 *
6696 * @version New in 1.11
6697 */
6698krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
6699krb5_responder_set_answer(krb5_context ctx, krb5_responder_context rctx,
6700 const char *question, const char *answer);
6701
6702/**
6703 * Responder function for an initial credential exchange.
6704 *
6705 * @param [in] ctx Library context
6706 * @param [in] data Callback data
6707 * @param [in] rctx Responder context
6708 *
6709 * A responder function is like a prompter function, but is used for handling
6710 * questions and answers as potentially complex data types. Client
6711 * preauthentication modules will insert a set of named "questions" into
6712 * the responder context. Each question may optionally contain a challenge.
6713 * This challenge is printable UTF-8, but may be an encoded value. The
6714 * precise encoding and contents of the challenge are specific to the question
6715 * asked. When the responder is called, it should answer all the questions it
6716 * understands. Like the challenge, the answer MUST be printable UTF-8, but
6717 * may contain structured/encoded data formatted to the expected answer format
6718 * of the question.
6719 *
6720 * If a required question is unanswered, the prompter may be called.
6721 */
6722typedef krb5_error_code
6723(KRB5_CALLCONV *krb5_responder_fn)(krb5_context ctx, void *data,
6724 krb5_responder_context rctx);
6725

6729 krb5_int32 length; /* -1 when not specified. */
6730 char *vendor;
6731 char *challenge;
6732 char *token_id;
6733 char *alg_id;
6734} krb5_responder_otp_tokeninfo;

6739} krb5_responder_otp_challenge;

7067/**

7071 * @param [in] opt Options
7072 * @param [in] fast_ccache_name Credential cache name
7073 *
7074 * Sets the location of a credential cache containing an armor ticket to
7075 * protect an initial credential exchange using the FAST protocol extension.
7076 *
7077 * In version 1.7, setting an armor ccache requires that FAST be used for the

7104/**
7105 * Set an input credential cache in initial credential options.
7106 *
7107 * @param [in] context Library context
7108 * @param [in] opt Options
7109 * @param [in] ccache Credential cache handle
7110 *
7111 * If an input credential cache is set, then the krb5_get_init_creds family of
7112 * APIs will read settings from it. Setting an input ccache is desirable when
7113 * the application wishes to perform authentication in the same way (using the
7114 * same preauthentication mechanisms, and making the same non-security-
7115 * sensitive choices) as the previous authentication attempt, which stored
7116 * information in the passed-in ccache.

7129 * @param [in] opt Options
7130 * @param [in] ccache Credential cache handle
7131 *
7132 * If an output credential cache is set, then the krb5_get_init_creds family of
7133 * APIs will write credentials to it. Setting an output ccache is desirable
7134 * both because it simplifies calling code and because it permits the
7135 * krb5_get_init_creds APIs to write out configuration information about the
7136 * realm to the ccache.

7149 *
7150 * If this option is set, the AS request will include a PAC-REQUEST pa-data
7151 * item explicitly asking the KDC to either include or not include a privilege
7152 * attribute certificate in the ticket authorization data. By default, no

7198
7199typedef void
7200(KRB5_CALLCONV *krb5_expire_callback_func)(krb5_context context, void *data,
7201 krb5_timestamp password_expiration,
7202 krb5_timestamp account_expiration,
7203 krb5_boolean is_last_req);
7204
7205/**
7206 * Set an expiration callback in initial credential options.
7207 *
7208 * @param [in] context Library context
7209 * @param [in] opt Options structure
7210 * @param [in] cb Callback function
7211 * @param [in] data Callback argument
7212 *
7213 * Set a callback to receive password and account expiration times.
7214 *
7215 * This option only applies to krb5_get_init_creds_password(). @a cb will be
7216 * invoked if and only if credentials are successfully acquired. The callback
7217 * will receive the @a context from the krb5_get_init_creds_password() call and
7218 * the @a data argument supplied with this API. The remaining arguments should
7219 * be interpreted as follows:
7220 *
7221 * If @a is_last_req is true, then the KDC reply contained last-req entries
7222 * which unambiguously indicated the password expiration, account expiration,
7223 * or both. (If either value was not present, the corresponding argument will
7224 * be 0.) Furthermore, a non-zero @a password_expiration should be taken as a
7225 * suggestion from the KDC that a warning be displayed.
7226 *
7227 * If @a is_last_req is false, then @a account_expiration will be 0 and @a
7228 * password_expiration will contain the expiration time of either the password
7229 * or account, or 0 if no expiration time was indicated in the KDC reply. The
7230 * callback should independently decide whether to display a password
7231 * expiration warning.
7232 *
7233 * Note that @a cb may be invoked even if credentials are being acquired for
7234 * the kadmin/changepw service in order to change the password. It is the
7235 * caller's responsibility to avoid displaying a password expiry warning in
7236 * this case.
7237 *
7238 * @warning Setting an expire callback with this API will cause
7239 * krb5_get_init_creds_password() not to send password expiry warnings to the
7240 * prompter, as it ordinarily may.
7241 *
7242 * @version New in 1.9
7243 */
7244krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
7245krb5_get_init_creds_opt_set_expire_callback(krb5_context context,
7246 krb5_get_init_creds_opt *opt,
7247 krb5_expire_callback_func cb,
7248 void *data);
7249
7250/**
7251 * Set the responder function in initial credential options.
7252 *
7253 * @param [in] context Library context
7254 * @param [in] opt Options structure
7255 * @param [in] responder Responder function
7256 * @param [in] data Responder data argument
7257 *
7258 * @version New in 1.11
7259 */
7260krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
7261krb5_get_init_creds_opt_set_responder(krb5_context context,
7262 krb5_get_init_creds_opt *opt,
7263 krb5_responder_fn responder, void *data);
7264
7265/**
7266 * Get initial credentials using a password.
7267 *
7268 * @param [in] context Library context
7269 * @param [out] creds New credentials
7270 * @param [in] client Client principal
7271 * @param [in] password Password (or NULL)
7272 * @param [in] prompter Prompter function
7273 * @param [in] data Prompter callback data
7274 * @param [in] start_time Time when ticket becomes valid (0 for now)
7275 * @param [in] in_tkt_service Service name of initial credentials (or NULL)
7276 * @param [in] k5_gic_options Initial credential options
7277 *
7278 * This function requests KDC for an initial credentials for @a client using @a
7279 * password. If @a password is NULL, a password will be prompted for using @a
7280 * prompter if necessary. If @a in_tkt_service is specified, it is parsed as a
7281 * principal name (with the realm ignored) and used as the service principal
7282 * for the request; otherwise the ticket-granting service is used.
7283 *
7284 * @sa krb5_verify_init_creds()
7285 *
7286 * @retval
7287 * 0 Success
7288 * @retval
7289 * EINVAL Invalid argument
7290 * @retval
7291 * KRB5_KDC_UNREACH Cannot contact any KDC for requested realm
7292 * @retval
7293 * KRB5_PREAUTH_FAILED Generic Pre-athentication failure
7294 * @retval
7295 * KRB5_LIBOS_PWDINTR Password read interrupted
7296 * @retval
7297 * KRB5_REALM_CANT_RESOLVE Cannot resolve network address for KDC in requested realm
7298 * @retval
7299 * KRB5KDC_ERR_KEY_EXP Password has expired
7300 * @retval
7301 * KRB5_LIBOS_BADPWDMATCH Password mismatch
7302 * @retval
7303 * KRB5_CHPW_PWDNULL New password cannot be zero length
7304 * @retval
7305 * KRB5_CHPW_FAIL Password change failed
7306 * @return
7307 * Kerberos error codes
7308 */
7309krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
7310krb5_get_init_creds_password(krb5_context context, krb5_creds *creds,
7311 krb5_principal client, const char *password,
7312 krb5_prompter_fct prompter, void *data,
7313 krb5_deltat start_time,
7314 const char *in_tkt_service,
7315 krb5_get_init_creds_opt *k5_gic_options);

7415/**
7416 * Get the next KDC request for acquiring initial credentials.
7417 *
7418 * @param [in] context Library context
7419 * @param [in] ctx Initial credentials context
7420 * @param [in] in KDC response (empty on the first call)
7421 * @param [out] out Next KDC request
7422 * @param [out] realm Realm for next KDC request
7423 * @param [out] flags Output flags
7424 *
7425 * This function constructs the next KDC request in an initial credential
7426 * exchange, allowing the caller to control the transport of KDC requests and
7427 * replies. On the first call, @a in should be set to an empty buffer; on
7428 * subsequent calls, it should be set to the KDC's reply to the previous
7429 * request.
7430 *
7431 * If more requests are needed, @a flags will be set to
7432 * #KRB5_INIT_CREDS_STEP_FLAG_CONTINUE and the next request will be placed in
7433 * @a out. If no more requests are needed, @a flags will not contain
7434 * #KRB5_INIT_CREDS_STEP_FLAG_CONTINUE and @a out will be empty.
7435 *
7436 * If this function returns @c KRB5KRB_ERR_RESPONSE_TOO_BIG, the caller should
7437 * transmit the next request using TCP rather than UDP. If this function
7438 * returns any other error, the initial credential exchange has failed.
7439 *
7440 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
7441 */
7442krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
7443krb5_init_creds_step(krb5_context context, krb5_init_creds_context ctx,
7444 krb5_data *in, krb5_data *out, krb5_data *realm,
7445 unsigned int *flags);
7446
7447/**
7448 * Set a password for acquiring initial credentials.
7449 *
7450 * @param [in] context Library context
7451 * @param [in] ctx Initial credentials context
7452 * @param [in] password Password
7453 *
7454 * This function supplies a password to be used to construct the client key for
7455 * an initial credentials request.
7456 *
7457 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
7458 */
7459krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
7460krb5_init_creds_set_password(krb5_context context, krb5_init_creds_context ctx,
7461 const char *password);
7462
7463/**
7464 * Specify a service principal for acquiring initial credentials.

7467 * @param [in] ctx Initial credentials context

7469 *
7470 * This function supplies a service principal string to acquire initial
7471 * credentials for instead of the default krbtgt service. @a service is parsed
7472 * as a principal name; any realm part is ignored.
7473 *
7474 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
7475 */
7476krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
7477krb5_init_creds_set_service(krb5_context context, krb5_init_creds_context ctx,

7499/**
7500 * Create a context to get credentials from a KDC's Ticket Granting Service.
7501 *
7502 * @param[in] context Library context
7503 * @param[in] ccache Credential cache handle
7504 * @param[in] creds Input credentials
7505 * @param[in] options @ref KRB5_GC options for this request.
7506 * @param[out] ctx New TGS request context
7507 *
7508 * This function prepares to obtain credentials matching @a creds, either by
7509 * retrieving them from @a ccache or by making requests to ticket-granting
7510 * services beginning with a ticket-granting ticket for the client principal's
7511 * realm.
7512 *
7513 * The resulting TGS acquisition context can be used asynchronously with
7514 * krb5_tkt_creds_step() or synchronously with krb5_tkt_creds_get(). See also
7515 * krb5_get_credentials() for synchronous use.
7516 *
7517 * Use krb5_tkt_creds_free() to free @a ctx when it is no longer needed.
7518 *
7519 * @version New in 1.9
7520 *
7521 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
7522 */
7523krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
7524krb5_tkt_creds_init(krb5_context context, krb5_ccache ccache,
7525 krb5_creds *creds, krb5_flags options,
7526 krb5_tkt_creds_context *ctx);
7527
7528/**

7530 *
7531 * @param[in] context Library context
7532 * @param[in] ctx TGS request context
7533 *
7534 * This function synchronously obtains credentials using a context created by
7535 * krb5_tkt_creds_init(). On successful return, the credentials can be
7536 * retrieved with krb5_tkt_creds_get_creds().
7537 *
7538 * @version New in 1.9
7539 *
7540 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
7541 */
7542krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
7543krb5_tkt_creds_get(krb5_context context, krb5_tkt_creds_context ctx);
7544
7545/**
7546 * Retrieve acquired credentials from a TGS request context.
7547 *
7548 * @param[in] context Library context
7549 * @param[in] ctx TGS request context
7550 * @param[out] creds Acquired credentials
7551 *
7552 * This function copies the acquired initial credentials from @a ctx into @a
7553 * creds, after the successful completion of krb5_tkt_creds_get() or
7554 * krb5_tkt_creds_step(). Use krb5_free_cred_contents() to free @a creds when
7555 * it is no longer needed.

7557 * @version New in 1.9

7573void KRB5_CALLCONV
7574krb5_tkt_creds_free(krb5_context context, krb5_tkt_creds_context ctx);

7576#define KRB5_TKT_CREDS_STEP_FLAG_CONTINUE 0x1 /**< More responses needed */
7577
7578/**
7579 * Get the next KDC request in a TGS exchange.
7580 *
7581 * @param[in] context Library context
7582 * @param[in] ctx TGS request context
7583 * @param[in] in KDC response (empty on the first call)
7584 * @param[out] out Next KDC request
7585 * @param[out] realm Realm for next KDC request
7586 * @param[out] flags Output flags
7587 *
7588 * This function constructs the next KDC request for a TGS exchange, allowing
7589 * the caller to control the transport of KDC requests and replies. On the
7590 * first call, @a in should be set to an empty buffer; on subsequent calls, it
7591 * should be set to the KDC's reply to the previous request.
7592 *
7593 * If more requests are needed, @a flags will be set to
7594 * #KRB5_TKT_CREDS_STEP_FLAG_CONTINUE and the next request will be placed in @a
7595 * out. If no more requests are needed, @a flags will not contain
7596 * #KRB5_TKT_CREDS_STEP_FLAG_CONTINUE and @a out will be empty.
7597 *
7598 * If this function returns @c KRB5KRB_ERR_RESPONSE_TOO_BIG, the caller should
7599 * transmit the next request using TCP rather than UDP. If this function
7600 * returns any other error, the TGS exchange has failed.
7601 *
7602 * @version New in 1.9
7603 *
7604 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
7605 */
7606krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
7607krb5_tkt_creds_step(krb5_context context, krb5_tkt_creds_context ctx,
7608 krb5_data *in, krb5_data *out, krb5_data *realm,
7609 unsigned int *flags);
7610
7611/**
7612 * Retrieve ticket times from a TGS request context.
7613 *
7614 * @param[in] context Library context
7615 * @param[in] ctx TGS request context
7616 * @param[out] times Ticket times for acquired credentials
7617 *
7618 * The TGS request context must have completed obtaining credentials via either
7619 * krb5_tkt_creds_get() or krb5_tkt_creds_step().
7620 *
7621 * @version New in 1.9
7622 *
7623 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
7624 */
7625krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
7626krb5_tkt_creds_get_times(krb5_context context, krb5_tkt_creds_context ctx,
7627 krb5_ticket_times *times);
7628
7629/**
7630 * Get initial credentials using a key table.
7631 *
7632 * @param [in] context Library context
7633 * @param [out] creds New credentials
7634 * @param [in] client Client principal
7635 * @param [in] arg_keytab Key table handle
7636 * @param [in] start_time Time when ticket becomes valid (0 for now)
7637 * @param [in] in_tkt_service Service name of initial credentials (or NULL)
7638 * @param [in] k5_gic_options Initial credential options
7639 *
7640 * This function requests KDC for an initial credentials for @a client using a
7641 * client key stored in @a arg_keytab. If @a in_tkt_service is specified, it
7642 * is parsed as a principal name (with the realm ignored) and used as the
7643 * service principal for the request; otherwise the ticket-granting service is
7644 * used.
7645 *
7646 * @sa krb5_verify_init_creds()
7647 *
7648 * @retval
7649 * 0 Success
7650 * @return
7651 * Kerberos error codes
7652 */
7653krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
7654krb5_get_init_creds_keytab(krb5_context context, krb5_creds *creds,
7655 krb5_principal client, krb5_keytab arg_keytab,
7656 krb5_deltat start_time, const char *in_tkt_service,
7657 krb5_get_init_creds_opt *k5_gic_options);
7658
7659typedef struct _krb5_verify_init_creds_opt {
7660 krb5_flags flags;
7661 int ap_req_nofail; /**< boolean */
7662} krb5_verify_init_creds_opt;
7663
7664#define KRB5_VERIFY_INIT_CREDS_OPT_AP_REQ_NOFAIL 0x0001
7665
7666/**
7667 * Initialize a credential verification options structure.
7668 *
7669 * @param [in] k5_vic_options Verification options structure
7670 */
7671void KRB5_CALLCONV
7672krb5_verify_init_creds_opt_init(krb5_verify_init_creds_opt *k5_vic_options);
7673
7674/**
7675 * Set whether credential verification is required.
7676 *
7677 * @param [in] k5_vic_options Verification options structure
7678 * @param [in] ap_req_nofail Whether to require successful verification
7679 *
7680 * This function determines how krb5_verify_init_creds() behaves if no keytab
7681 * information is available. If @a ap_req_nofail is @c FALSE, verification
7682 * will be skipped in this case and krb5_verify_init_creds() will return
7683 * successfully. If @a ap_req_nofail is @c TRUE, krb5_verify_init_creds() will
7684 * not return successfully unless verification can be performed.
7685 *
7686 * If this function is not used, the behavior of krb5_verify_init_creds() is
7687 * determined through configuration.
7688 */
7689void KRB5_CALLCONV
7690krb5_verify_init_creds_opt_set_ap_req_nofail(krb5_verify_init_creds_opt * k5_vic_options,
7691 int ap_req_nofail);
7692
7693/**
7694 * Verify initial credentials against a keytab.
7695 *
7696 * @param [in] context Library context
7697 * @param [in] creds Initial credentials to be verified
7698 * @param [in] server Server principal (or NULL)
7699 * @param [in] keytab Key table (NULL to use default keytab)
7700 * @param [in] ccache Credential cache for fetched creds (or NULL)
7701 * @param [in] options Verification options (NULL for default options)
7702 *
7703 * This function attempts to verify that @a creds were obtained from a KDC with
7704 * knowledge of a key in @a keytab, or the default keytab if @a keytab is NULL.
7705 * If @a server is provided, the highest-kvno key entry for that principal name
7706 * is used to verify the credentials; otherwise, all unique "host" service
7707 * principals in the keytab are tried.
7708 *
7709 * If the specified keytab does not exist, or is empty, or cannot be read, or
7710 * does not contain an entry for @a server, then credential verification may be
7711 * skipped unless configuration demands that it succeed. The caller can
7712 * control this behavior by providing a verification options structure; see
7713 * krb5_verify_init_creds_opt_init() and
7714 * krb5_verify_init_creds_opt_set_ap_req_nofail().
7715 *
7716 * If @a ccache is NULL, any additional credentials fetched during the
7717 * verification process will be destroyed. If @a ccache points to NULL, a
7718 * memory ccache will be created for the additional credentials and returned in
7719 * @a ccache. If @a ccache points to a valid credential cache handle, the
7720 * additional credentials will be stored in that cache.
7721 *
7722 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
7723 */
7724krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
7725krb5_verify_init_creds(krb5_context context, krb5_creds *creds,
7726 krb5_principal server, krb5_keytab keytab,
7727 krb5_ccache *ccache,
7728 krb5_verify_init_creds_opt *options);
7729
7730/**
7731 * Get validated credentials from the KDC.
7732 *
7733 * @param [in] context Library context
7734 * @param [out] creds Validated credentials
7735 * @param [in] client Client principal name
7736 * @param [in] ccache Credential cache
7737 * @param [in] in_tkt_service Server principal string (or NULL)
7738 *
7739 * This function gets a validated credential using a postdated credential from
7740 * @a ccache. If @a in_tkt_service is specified, it is parsed (with the realm
7741 * part ignored) and used as the server principal of the credential;
7742 * otherwise, the ticket-granting service is used.
7743 *
7744 * If successful, the validated credential is placed in @a creds.
7745 *
7746 * @sa krb5_get_renewed_creds()
7747 *
7748 * @retval
7749 * 0 Success
7750 * @retval
7751 * KRB5_NO_2ND_TKT Request missing second ticket
7752 * @retval
7753 * KRB5_NO_TKT_SUPPLIED Request did not supply a ticket
7754 * @retval
7755 * KRB5_PRINC_NOMATCH Requested principal and ticket do not match
7756 * @retval
7757 * KRB5_KDCREP_MODIFIED KDC reply did not match expectations
7758 * @retval
7759 * KRB5_KDCREP_SKEW Clock skew too great in KDC reply
7760 * @return
7761 * Kerberos error codes
7762 */
7763krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
7764krb5_get_validated_creds(krb5_context context, krb5_creds *creds,
7765 krb5_principal client, krb5_ccache ccache,
7766 const char *in_tkt_service);
7767
7768/**
7769 * Get renewed credential from KDC using an existing credential.
7770 *
7771 * @param [in] context Library context
7772 * @param [out] creds Renewed credentials
7773 * @param [in] client Client principal name
7774 * @param [in] ccache Credential cache
7775 * @param [in] in_tkt_service Server principal string (or NULL)
7776 *
7777 * This function gets a renewed credential using an existing one from @a
7778 * ccache. If @a in_tkt_service is specified, it is parsed (with the realm
7779 * part ignored) and used as the server principal of the credential; otherwise,
7780 * the ticket-granting service is used.
7781 *
7782 * If successful, the renewed credential is placed in @a creds.
7783 *
7784 * @retval
7785 * 0 Success
7786 * @return
7787 * Kerberos error codes
7788 */
7789krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
7790krb5_get_renewed_creds(krb5_context context, krb5_creds *creds,
7791 krb5_principal client, krb5_ccache ccache,
7792 const char *in_tkt_service);
7793
7794/**
7795 * Decode an ASN.1-formatted ticket.
7796 *
7797 * @param [in] code ASN.1-formatted ticket
7798 * @param [out] rep Decoded ticket information

7800 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
7801 */
7802krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
7803krb5_decode_ticket(const krb5_data *code, krb5_ticket **rep);

7866 * prompts arguments. Each type has one of the following values:

7868 * @li #KRB5_PROMPT_TYPE_NEW_PASSWORD
7869 * @li #KRB5_PROMPT_TYPE_NEW_PASSWORD_AGAIN

7963#endif

7999 * @param [in] code Error code
8000 *
8001 * The behavior of krb5_get_error_message() is only defined the first time it
8002 * is called after a failed call to a krb5 function using the same context, and
8003 * only when the error code passed in is the same as that returned by the krb5
8004 * function.
8005 *
8006 * This function never returns NULL, so its result may be used unconditionally
8007 * as a C string.
8008 *
8009 * The string returned by this function must be freed using
8010 * krb5_free_error_message()
8011 *
8012 * @note Future versions may return the same string for the second
8013 * and following calls.
8014 */
8015const char * KRB5_CALLCONV
8016krb5_get_error_message(krb5_context ctx, krb5_error_code code);

8106 *

8119/*
8120 * Windows PAC
8121 */
8122
8123/* Microsoft defined types of data */
8124#define KRB5_PAC_LOGON_INFO 1 /**< Logon information */
8125#define KRB5_PAC_CREDENTIALS_INFO 2 /**< Credentials information */
8126#define KRB5_PAC_SERVER_CHECKSUM 6 /**< Server checksum */
8127#define KRB5_PAC_PRIVSVR_CHECKSUM 7 /**< KDC checksum */
8128#define KRB5_PAC_CLIENT_INFO 10 /**< Client name and ticket info */
8129#define KRB5_PAC_DELEGATION_INFO 11 /**< Constrained delegation info */
8130#define KRB5_PAC_UPN_DNS_INFO 12 /**< User principal name and DNS info */
8131
8132struct krb5_pac_data;
8133/** PAC data structure to convey authorization information */
8134typedef struct krb5_pac_data *krb5_pac;
8135
8136/**
8137 * Add a buffer to a PAC handle.
8138 *
8139 * @param [in] context Library context
8140 * @param [in] pac PAC handle
8141 * @param [in] type Buffer type
8142 * @param [in] data contents
8143 *
8144 * This function adds a buffer of type @a type and contents @a data to @a pac
8145 * if there isn't already a buffer of this type present.
8146 *
8147 * The valid values of @a type is one of the following:
8148 * @li #KRB5_PAC_LOGON_INFO - Logon information
8149 * @li #KRB5_PAC_CREDENTIALS_INFO - Credentials information
8150 * @li #KRB5_PAC_SERVER_CHECKSUM - Server checksum
8151 * @li #KRB5_PAC_PRIVSVR_CHECKSUM - KDC checksum
8152 * @li #KRB5_PAC_CLIENT_INFO - Client name and ticket information
8153 * @li #KRB5_PAC_DELEGATION_INFO - Constrained delegation information
8154 * @li #KRB5_PAC_UPN_DNS_INFO - User principal name and DNS information
8155 *
8156 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
8157 */
8158krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
8159krb5_pac_add_buffer(krb5_context context, krb5_pac pac, krb5_ui_4 type,
8160 const krb5_data *data);

8231
8232/**
8233 * Verify a PAC.
8234 *
8235 * @param [in] context Library context
8236 * @param [in] pac PAC handle
8237 * @param [in] authtime Expected timestamp
8238 * @param [in] principal Expected principal name (or NULL)
8239 * @param [in] server Key to validate server checksum (or NULL)
8240 * @param [in] privsvr Key to validate KDC checksum (or NULL)
8241 *
8242 * This function validates @a pac against the supplied @a server, @a privsvr,
8243 * @a principal and @a authtime. If @a principal is NULL, the principal and
8244 * authtime are not verified. If @a server or @a privsvr is NULL, the
8245 * corresponding checksum is not verified.
8246 *
8247 * If successful, @a pac is marked as verified.
8248 *
8249 * @note A checksum mismatch can occur if the PAC was copied from a cross-realm
8250 * TGT by an ignorant KDC; also Apple Mac OS X Server Open Directory (as of
8251 * 10.6) generates PACs with no server checksum at all. One should consider
8252 * not failing the whole authentication because of this reason, but, instead,
8253 * treating the ticket as if it did not contain a PAC or marking the PAC
8254 * information as non-verified.
8255 *
8256 * @retval 0 Success; otherwise - Kerberos error codes
8257 */
8258krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
8259krb5_pac_verify(krb5_context context, const krb5_pac pac,
8260 krb5_timestamp authtime, krb5_const_principal principal,
8261 const krb5_keyblock *server, const krb5_keyblock *privsvr);
8262
8263/**
8264 * Sign a PAC.
8265 *
8266 * @param [in] context Library context
8267 * @param [in] pac PAC handle
8268 * @param [in] authtime Expected timestamp
8269 * @param [in] principal Expected principal name (or NULL)
8270 * @param [in] server_key Key for server checksum
8271 * @param [in] privsvr_key Key for KDC checksum
8272 * @param [out] data Signed PAC encoding
8273 *
8274 * This function signs @a pac using the keys @a server_key and @a privsvr_key
8275 * and returns the signed encoding in @a data. @a pac is modified to include
8276 * the server and KDC checksum buffers. Use krb5_free_data_contents() to free
8277 * @a data when it is no longer needed.
8278 *
8279 * @version New in 1.10
8280 */
8281krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
8282krb5_pac_sign(krb5_context context, krb5_pac pac, krb5_timestamp authtime,
8283 krb5_const_principal principal, const krb5_keyblock *server_key,
8284 const krb5_keyblock *privsvr_key, krb5_data *data);

8300/**
8301 * A wrapper for passing information to a @c krb5_trace_callback.
8302 *
8303 * Currently, it only contains the formatted message as determined
8304 * the the format string and arguments of the tracing macro, but it
8305 * may be extended to contain more fields in the future.
8306 */
8307typedef struct _krb5_trace_info {
8308 const char *message;
8309} krb5_trace_info;
8310
8311typedef void
8312(KRB5_CALLCONV *krb5_trace_callback)(krb5_context context,
8313 const krb5_trace_info *info,
8314 void *cb_data);

8316/**
8317 * Specify a callback function for trace events.
8318 *
8319 * @param [in] context Library context
8320 * @param [in] fn Callback function
8321 * @param [in] cb_data Callback data
8322 *
8323 * Specify a callback for trace events occurring in krb5 operations performed
8324 * within @a context. @a fn will be invoked with @a context as the first
8325 * argument, @a cb_data as the last argument, and a pointer to a
8326 * krb5_trace_info as the second argument. If the trace callback is reset via
8327 * this function or @a context is destroyed, @a fn will be invoked with a NULL
8328 * second argument so it can clean up @a cb_data. Supply a NULL value for @a
8329 * fn to disable trace callbacks within @a context.
8330 *
8331 * @note This function overrides the information passed through the
8332 * @a KRB5_TRACE environment variable.
8333 *
8334 * @version New in 1.9
8335 *
8336 * @return Returns KRB5_TRACE_NOSUPP if tracing is not supported in the library
8337 * (unless @a fn is NULL).
8338 */
8339krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
8340krb5_set_trace_callback(krb5_context context, krb5_trace_callback fn,
8341 void *cb_data);

8344 * Specify a file name for directing trace events.
8345 *
8346 * @param [in] context Library context
8347 * @param [in] filename File name
8348 *
8349 * Open @a filename for appending (creating it, if necessary) and set up a
8350 * callback to write trace events to it.
8351 *
8352 * @note This function overrides the information passed through the

8359krb5_error_code KRB5_CALLCONV
8360krb5_set_trace_filename(krb5_context context, const char *filename);

8362
8363/**
8364 * Hook function for inspecting or modifying messages sent to KDCs.
8365 *
8366 * @param [in] context Library context
8367 * @param [in] data Callback data
8368 * @param [in] realm The realm the message will be sent to
8369 * @param [in] message The original message to be sent to the KDC
8370 * @param [out] new_message_out Optional replacement message to be sent
8371 * @param [out] reply_out Optional synthetic reply
8372 *
8373 * If the hook function returns an error code, the KDC communication will be
8374 * aborted and the error code will be returned to the library operation which
8375 * initiated the communication.
8376 *
8377 * If the hook function sets @a reply_out, @a message will not be sent to the
8378 * KDC, and the given reply will used instead.
8379 *
8380 * If the hook function sets @a new_message_out, the given message will be sent
8381 * to the KDC in place of @a message.
8382 *
8383 * If the hook function returns successfully without setting either output,
8384 * @a message will be sent to the KDC normally.
8385 *
8386 * The hook function should use krb5_copy_data() to construct the value for
8387 * @a new_message_out or @a reply_out, to ensure that it can be freed correctly
8388 * by the library.
8389 *
8390 * @version New in 1.15
8391 *
8392 * @retval 0 Success
8393 * @return A Kerberos error code
8394 */
8395typedef krb5_error_code
8396(KRB5_CALLCONV *krb5_pre_send_fn)(krb5_context context, void *data,
8397 const krb5_data *realm,
8398 const krb5_data *message,
8399 krb5_data **new_message_out,
8400 krb5_data **new_reply_out);
8401
8402/**
8403 * Hook function for inspecting or overriding KDC replies.
8404 *
8405 * @param [in] context Library context
8406 * @param [in] data Callback data
8407 * @param [in] code Status of KDC communication
8408 * @param [in] realm The realm the reply was received from
8409 * @param [in] message The message sent to the realm's KDC
8410 * @param [in] reply The reply received from the KDC
8411 * @param [out] new_reply_out Optional replacement reply
8412 *
8413 * If @a code is zero, @a reply contains the reply received from the KDC. The
8414 * hook function may return an error code to simulate an error, may synthesize
8415 * a different reply by setting @a new_reply_out, or may simply return
8416 * successfully to do nothing.
8417 *
8418 * If @a code is non-zero, KDC communication failed and @a reply should be
8419 * ignored. The hook function may return @a code or a different error code, or
8420 * may synthesize a reply by setting @a new_reply_out and return successfully.
8421 *
8422 * The hook function should use krb5_copy_data() to construct the value for
8423 * @a new_reply_out, to ensure that it can be freed correctly by the library.
8424 *
8425 * @version New in 1.15
8426 *
8427 * @retval 0 Success
8428 * @return A Kerberos error code
8429 */
8430typedef krb5_error_code
8431(KRB5_CALLCONV *krb5_post_recv_fn)(krb5_context context, void *data,
8432 krb5_error_code code,
8433 const krb5_data *realm,
8434 const krb5_data *message,
8435 const krb5_data *reply,
8436 krb5_data **new_reply_out);
8437
8438/**
8439 * Set a KDC pre-send hook function.
8440 *
8441 * @param [in] context Library context
8442 * @param [in] send_hook Hook function (or NULL to disable the hook)
8443 * @param [in] data Callback data to be passed to @a send_hook
8444 *
8445 * @a send_hook will be called before messages are sent to KDCs by library
8446 * functions such as krb5_get_credentials(). The hook function may inspect,
8447 * override, or synthesize its own reply to the message.
8448 *
8449 * @version New in 1.15
8450 */
8451void KRB5_CALLCONV
8452krb5_set_kdc_send_hook(krb5_context context, krb5_pre_send_fn send_hook,
8453 void *data);
8454
8455/**
8456 * Set a KDC post-receive hook function.
8457 *
8458 * @param [in] context The library context.
8459 * @param [in] recv_hook Hook function (or NULL to disable the hook)
8460 * @param [in] data Callback data to be passed to @a recv_hook
8461 *
8462 * @a recv_hook will be called after a reply is received from a KDC during a
8463 * call to a library function such as krb5_get_credentials(). The hook
8464 * function may inspect or override the reply. This hook will not be executed
8465 * if the pre-send hook returns a synthetic reply.
8466 *
8467 * @version New in 1.15
8468 */
8469void KRB5_CALLCONV
8470krb5_set_kdc_recv_hook(krb5_context context, krb5_post_recv_fn recv_hook,
8471 void *data);
